<FIRST>r i PM-Poland'sProspects     09-17 0922</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland's Prospects,0953</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mazowiecki's Economic Challenge Hard To Over Estimate</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DRUSILLA MENAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If Poland's historic transition to
democracy is to survive, the new government must quickly solve some
serious economic problems.
   Yet the dimensions and complexity of the crisis are so staggering
that even Solidarity's Tadeusz Mazowiecki, the first non-Communist
prime minister in the East bloc, says ``Society has no concept how
difficult it will be to reform this economy.''
   How bad is it? Consider:
   The value of the zloty currency continues to plummet as inflation
soars. At the end of June, 4,900 zloties bought a dollar. Last week,
it took 10,000.
   That means a man who receives $20 a month from an aunt in Chicago
gets more than a month's average wage, which was 122,000 zlotys in
July, up from 55,000 in January.
   As a result, workers by the score have walked away from their
state jobs, forcing shops to close, mail to go undelivered and
assembly lines to stall.
   This year's state budget envisioned a deficit equivalent to $989
million at the official exchange rate, but the government raised it
to $4.9 billion in just seven months, said economics Professor Jozef
Kaleta in the Express Wieczorny newspaper.
   To span he gap, the government issues more money. Nearly 45
percent of the budget is being covered by the printing of banknotes,
according to a Communist Party report.
   The list of basics available only with difficulty this week in
Warsaw includes flour, cheese, sugar, razor blades, matches, washing
powder and sanitary napkins.
   The government survey of the ``mounting disequilibrium'' in the
non-food market listed as ``particularly painful'' shortages of
clothing, footwear, furniture, consumer electronics, appliances,
refrigerators, kitchenware, radios, sewing machines, bicycles, cars,
soap and shampoo.
   ``I have two children and I literally live in front of this store
for three weeks because my refrigerator broke down,'' said a woman
who, at 11:30 p.m., was in line outside a Warsaw shop where a
shipment of new appliances was expected some day. She and other
relatives took turns sleeping in a car.
   The hopelessly inadequate telephone system has less than 3
million telephones for 38 million people, no direct connections to
the United States and a tendency to cut off whole districts where
numbers start with a certain digit.
   Poland's $39 billion on foreign debt, $1,026 for every man, woman
and child, is the fourth largest in the world after Brazil, Mexico
and Argentina.
   Thirty percent of the government budget subsidizes goods and
services, according to a World Bank report.
   The cost of producing beef and veal is 50 percent subsidized,
according to the report. Such subsidies mean a farmer could find it
cheaper to buy milk at a store than drink it from his own cows.
   With the average price for coal covering only 53 percent of
production costs, supplies for the approaching winter are down
dramatically for lack of government subsidies, the state news agency
PAP warns. Other state industries can't pay for their coal.
   Outmoded, inefficient factories should be closed. But they employ
huge work forces, making up much of Solidarity's membership, and the
critical housing shortage makes it difficult for displaced workers
to move to new jobs.
   The wait for a minuscule Warsaw apartment is a decade or more,
but this year forecasters expect to complete 30,000 housing units
less than planned nationwide.
   Typical is a 20-year-old high rise apartment house on Dolna
Street in Warsaw which has not had hot water for seven of the past
11 months due to shoddy construction and lack of spare parts. Five
older neighboring buildings are not equipped for hot water at all.
   About 20 percent of university students emigrate, Gazeta Wyborcza
says.
   Doctors frequently prescribe medicines not available at
pharmacies, relying on patients to secure them in the West.
   Hospital stays require a supply of gifts to the staff to secure
everything from clean sheets to anesthetics.
   Physicians and nurses are among the most underpaid of Poles, a
remnant of the glorification of the laborer, and are allowed private
patients only after hours at government clinics.
   A dual currency system has developed, with the dollar used for
most meaningful transactions. Coffee, orange juice, Scotch,
televisions and apartments generally are available only for dollars.
   Most economic indicators are down, according to the most recent
government statistics: industrial sales by 5.9 percent,
manufacturing sales by 6 percent, June livestock procurement 25
percent below June 1988.
   Harder to quantify, but widely felt, is a decline in the pride of
craft as workers become demoralized.
   ``The present state of services, transportation, communications
and health care ... makes daily life extremely difficult, forces
people to break moral standards and accept humiliating treatment,''
wrote Stanislaw Chelstowski in Economic Life newspaper.
   The challenge is partly psychological, Mazowiecki says.
   ``The most difficult task is to make people feel that it can be
better, although it cannot be better immediately,'' he said.
   A 21-year-old teacher, learning of Mazowiecki's election,
commented: ``We're so tired, it doesn't really matter what happens.''
   On Aug. 1, the outgoing government took the first radical step,
lifting controls on almost all food prices. Although price increases
of several hundred percent followed, economists hope supplies will
improve.
   But a consensus is forming that even more painful and radical
reforms are needed.
   ``The economy is on its knees. The pauperization of society
advances almost from day to day so there is no time to look for some
miraculous cures,'' said Kaleta.
</TEXT>
