<FIRST>b a AM-MissAmerica 4thLd-Writethru a0647 09-17 1248</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Miss America, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0647,1284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Miss Missouri Named 1990 Miss America</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 28 grafs to add reaction quotes from winner and friends
and additional background; Debbye is cq. Picks up 21st graf pvs, `Ten finalists
...'; Expected to stand for AMs. Below dash material stands.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos XACC2, XACC3, XACC4, LaserColor XACC5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Miss Missouri Debbye Turner, a
marimba-playing veterinary student, was crowned Miss America 1990 on
Saturday night.
   Miss Turner grabbed and hugged first runner-up Miss Maryland
Virginia Cha, 25, of Frederick, and gave a thumbs-up sign to the
audience before tearfully walking the runway.
   The other contestants swarmed around her as she finished her walk.
   ``It's exhilarating. I can only compare it to being in the
Olympics,'' said Miss Turner, 23, of Mexico, Mo.
   The second runner-up was Miss Colorado Debbie Riecks, 24, of
Aurora; the third runner-up was Miss Illinois Jeri Lynn Zimmermann,
21, of Chicago; and the fourth runner-up was Miss Ohio Kristin
Huffman, 24, of Canal Winchester.
   Miss Turner is the third black woman to become Miss America in
the pageant's 68-year history. She succeeds Miss America 1989
Gretchen Elizabeth Carlson, 23, of Anoka, Minn.
   Miss Turner said she felt no added pressure being a black Miss
America.
   ``I'm Debbye Turner. I grew up in Arkansas. I attend school in
Missouri. I'm a born-again Christian,'' she said. ``That's who I am.
Being black is not who I am.''
   She said she could only attribute her victory to the ``grace of
God,'' and now that she has won, her plans include eating pepperoni
pizza and sleeping.
   Miss Carlson placed the crown on Miss Turner's head before
sending her walking down the runway in the Atlantic City Convention
Center as host Gary Collins sang the pageant standard, ``There She
Is.''
   This year's contest became a platform for social issues for the
first time. Each finalist was asked a question about the issue of
her choice.
   Miss Turner was asked how to best motivate America's youth.
   ``You have to let them know they can do anything and then show
them the way to do that,'' she said.
   The 5-foot-7{, 118-pound contestant with dark brown hair and
brown eyes won one of the three preliminary swimsuit competitions,
in which she wore a canary yellow swimsuit.
   Miss Turner said her studies as a senior at the University of
Missouri-Columbia Veterinary Shool have given her the opportunity to
treat ``everything from a 4-day-old Vietnamese pot-bellied piglet to
a 2,000-pound Hereford bull.'' She said she collects ``surgery
souvenirs'' such as puppy fetuses.
   ``I just have a pure love for animals,'' said Miss Turner, who
turns 24 on Tuesday.
   Miss Turner wowed the crowd by playing the rapid-fire ``Flight of
the Bumblebee'' on the marimba. Wearing a two-piece red chiffon
pants suit with silver beading and a peplum waistline, she used four
mallets for part of the number before tossing two of them behind her
in an intense performance.
   For the evening gown competition, she wore a white velvet beaded
gown with a rhinestone bodice. The V-neck gown featured a keyhole
back.
   Each contestant was asked to write an essay before the pageant to
detail what she would like to advocate during her year as Miss
America.
   Miss Turner, a poised, self-assured woman, has said she wants to
use her reign to motivate young students to strive higher.
   ``I'm not naive,'' she said before the pageant. ``If I win Miss
America, I'm not saying I'm going to change every youth. If I've
inspired one person to be an astronaut, then I'd feel I made a
difference.''
   She deflects criticisms that the pageant offers a chance only to
white women.
   ``The doors weren't closed to me,'' she said. ``It's open for any
woman who is talented.''
   There have been two black Miss Americas. Miss America 1984
Vanessa Williams, however, was dethroned after a men's magazine
published nude photos of her cavorting with another woman. The first
runner-up that year, Suzette Charles, was also black, and she
completed Miss Williams' reign.
   Black women were not allowed to enter the pageant for the first
three decades of the contest. Blacks portrayed slaves in crowning
ceremonies during the early years of the pageant.
   Miss Turner's father, Frederick, is a retired Army career
officer. Her mother, Gussie, is a counselor, a missionary and an
evangelist. She has a 27-year-old sister, Suzette.
   About 15 friends from Miss Turner's veterinary class at the
University of Missouri in Columbia attended a party to watch the
contest.
   ``Debbye has the morals, she has the talent and she's a
professional,'' said Linda Patton, a third-year veterinary student.
``It was exciting. It was a thrill just knowing she was there.''
   Ten finalists were announced early in the televised program. In
addition to the runners-up, the finalists were Miss Florida Sandra
Frick, 23, of Hialeah; Miss Oklahoma Tamara Denise Toshiko Marler,
26, of Tulsa; Miss Pennsylvania Michelle Kline, 24, of Easton; Miss
Texas Leah Kay Lyle, 22, of Plainview; and Miss Washington Jennifer
Wall, 20, of Issaquah.
   The 10 finalists had the highest scores after three days of
preliminary swimsuit, talent and evening gown competitions and
interviews with judges.
   All of this year's contestants were asked by pageant officials to
take a stand on the issue of their choice, and the winner will be
urged to promote her platform during her reign.
   Pageant director Leonard Horn said the idea of giving Miss
America a voice is one that might bring her more national respect.
He has stressed in the past several months that ``this is not just a
beauty pageant.''
   For the first time, the contestants this year had to submit an
essay on the an issue they planned to promote during their year's
reign.
   Some of the issues chosen among the 10 finalists included human
organ donation, volunteerism, better education for minority
students, accessibility for the disabled and discrimination.
   The festivities were marred Friday night when Miss Marler was
struck in the head with a beer bottle during the Miss America Parade
and suffered a concussion. She spent the night under observation at
a city hospital and returned to rehearsal Saturday morning.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The 68-year-old Miss America Pageant awards more than $5 million
in scholarships annually to more than 80,000 young women who compete
on the national, state and local levels.
   The new Miss America receives $42,500 in scholarships and the
next three runners-up receive $20,000, $14,000 and $11,000,
respectively.
   The remaining finalists each receive $6,000 to be used toward
their educations, and every remaining contestant receives a $2,500
scholarship.
   Collins was joined by his co-host, Miss America 1971 Phyllis
George Brown, for this year's show, an NBC-TV production with the
theme ``A Moment in Time.''
   The 51 contestants were interviewed and judged during the week by
a preliminary panel of seven judges. On Saturday, a panel of seven
celebrity judges started with a clean slate evaluating the 10
finalists.
   The scoring has been revised this year so that the interview with
the preliminary judges is counted in the final point tally Saturday
night. In the final scoring, talent counts for 40 percent, the
interview for 30 percent, and the evening gown and swimsuit
divisions each count for 15 percent.
   The celebrity judges were: developer Donald Trump, entertainer
and casino owner Merv Griffin, actresses Debbie Allen and Phylicia
Rashad, former Philadelphia Phillies third baseman Mike Schmidt,
psychologist and columnist Joyce Brothers, and gossip columnist
Claudia Cohen.
</TEXT>
