<FIRST>u i BC-MotherTeresa     09-17 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Mother Teresa,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nobel Laureate Having Chest Pains Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FARID HOSSAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CALCUTTA, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mother Teresa developed chest pains again
Sunday, but doctors treating the Nobel laureate said her overall
condition was stable.
   A statement issued by Woodlands Nursing Home, the hospital where
she is recovering from a heart attack, said the 79-year-old Roman
Catholic nun was ``resting comfortably.''
   ``The mother is having some chest pains. But her temperature is
showing signs of settling down and her overall condition is
stable,'' the statement said.
   ``We have found one or two causes for the infection. We are
hopeful that now she will improve faster,'' said Dr. A.K. Bardhan,
refusing to elaborate.
   Bardhan said Mother Teresa was still using a temporary pacemaker
that was attached after she suffered a heart attack Sept. 8. ``But
her heart is still weak even though she is improving and responding
to treatment,'' he said.
   Mother Teresa first developed chest pains and high fever Thursday
just as doctors thought she was progressing well.
   The soft-spoken nun was admitted to the hospital Sept. 5 with an
irregular heartbeat, a blocked artery and high fever.
   Born in Yugoslavia, Mother Teresa gave up a comfortable life as a
convent teacher to live and work among the destitute and dying in
this eastern Indian city's squalid slums. She was awarded the 1979
Nobel Peace Prize for her work.
   She founded the Missionaries of Charity in October 1950 in an
abandoned rundown hostel donated by the city. The order, formally
recognized by the Vatican in 1965, expanded and has 3,000 nuns
working in 87 countries.
</TEXT>
