<FIRST>u i BC-Britain-Tankers 3rdLd-Writethru   09-17 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Tankers, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0657,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Tankers Collide And Burn in North Sea, Causing 5-Mile Slick</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES to CORRECT that officials unsure how collision occurred,
UPDATES with gallons spilled. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HULL, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two oil tankers collided in the North Sea
off eastern England early Sunday, causing a fire aboard both vessels
and an oil slick five miles long, the coast guard said.
   Seventeen of 26 crew members were evacuated from the
Liberian-registered Phillips Oklahoma after it collided with the
Maltese-registered Fiona, anchored near the mouth of the Humber
River about 150 miles north of London, said spokesman David Clempson.
   The Fiona's bosun jumped overboard and was treated for shock
after he was rescued, but the rest of the ship's 30-member crew
remained aboard, Clempson said. No other injuries were reported.
   The collision caused about 340,000 gallons of crude oil to escape
from the Oklahoma, forming a slick about five miles long and a
quarter-mile wide before the leak was contained, said Clempson.
   ``Most of that will have probably been burnt up in the fire,'' he
said. ``The way it is heading it doesn't appear to be coming
ashore.''
   Clempson said aircraft were dispatched to spray chemicals to
disperse the oil.
   The fires were extinguished by mid-morning and both ships were
anchored off Spurn Head in the mouth of the Humber River, Clempson
said.
   The Phillips Oklahoma, laden with 56,000 tons of crude oil, and
the Fiona carrying 46,500 tons of refined oil collided at about 5
a.m. (midnight EDT Saturday), he said.
   ``I'm not going to be drawn on the question of who's
responsibility it was,'' he said, adding that the investigation
would be conducted by the Marine Accident Investigation branch of
the British Department of Transport.
   Clempson said it was not clear how the collision occurred, since
the Phillips Oklahoma, the moving ship, was damaged on the stern
while the Fiona was damaged on the bow.
   Humberside police said the Oklahoma was inward bound to discharge
its cargo.
   Sea King helicopters, a Nimrod reconnaissance aircraft, a Royal
Navy minesweeper and firefighting tugs took part in the rescue,
Clempson said.
</TEXT>
