<FIRST>r a BC-StaynerDeath     09-17 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Stayner Death,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kidnap Victim Steven Stayner Dead At 24</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MERCED, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steven Stayner, who as a child was
kidnapped and held captive until he escaped seven years later, died
in a motorcycle accident, a coroner's spokesman said.
   Stayner, 24, was pronounced dead at Merced Community Medical
Center shortly after the 5:30 p.m. Saturday accident on Santa Fe
Highway between Merced and Atwater, said a Merced County coroner's
spokesman, who declined to give his name.
   The car that hit Stayner, who was riding a motorcycle without a
helmet, took off after the accident, said state police officer Alan
Maxfield. It was found in Merced after the driver apparently
switched to another car, Maxfield said.
   Stayner, the subject of an NBC miniseries in May, lived as the
son of his abductor, Kenneth Parnell, a convicted child molester.
   In 1972, at the age of 7, Stayner was kidnapped while walking
home from school in Merced. When Stayner was 14, Parnell kidnapped
another boy, 5-year-old Timmy White. A short time later, Stayner
escaped, taking Timmy with him and going to a police station in
Ukiah, about 150 miles north.
   Stayner recently talked candidly with reporters of his life with
Parnell, who he said alternately molested him and passed him off as
his son, calling him Dennis. The boy was led to believe his parents
didn't want him any more.
   Parnell was convicted of two counts of kidnapping and was
sentenced to eight years and eight months in prison in February 1982
after an 18-day trial in Hayward. He served five years at Soledad
State Prison, then was on parole for another two years.
   While no sex charges were filed against Parnell, Stayner
testified during trial that he had been sexually abused.
   In 1985, Stayner married Jody Edmondson in Atwater, where the two
were living with their two small children at the time of his death.
   Earlier this year, Stayner had a walk-on part as a Merced police
officer in the television series about his case, ``I Know My First
Name is Steven,'' which was broadcast in May on NBC.
   In April, he told an interviewer, ``My hope with the movie is
that some kid sees it and gets up the nerve to tell someone and try
to come home.''
   Parnell, 57, is believed to be living in the San Francisco East
Bay area.
</TEXT>
