<FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-89 1204EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PatrickKennedy     09-17 0698</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Patrick Kennedy,0718</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Political Education of a Young Kennedy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FLIPPEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Growing up in America's most famous
political family did not prepare Patrick J. Kennedy for the ways of
the Rhode Island General Assembly.
   The political education of Sen. Edward Kennedy's younger son
began last year, when he challenged a 10-year incumbent in the
Democratic primary for a state House seat from northwest Providence.
It continued when he got to the Statehouse and learned what it
really takes to pass a bill.
   Kennedy, 22, was no ordinary freshman. Then a junior and now a
senior at Providence College, he spent $87,694, or $66 per vote _ a
record for a state legislative race _ for a job that pays $300 a
year. All but $5,904 of that was his own money.
   Then Kennedy hired a staff aide and opened an office in his
district. His predecessor, like most General Assembly members, had
operated alone, using space in his house and his funeral home.
   But despite his family's wealth and prominence, Kennedy soon
found his bills treated the same as everyone else's in a House
where, observers like the group Common Cause say, the speaker's word
is law.
   Several of Kennedy's major initiatives, including a bill to
require Rhode Island automobiles to adhere to California emissions
standards, never got out of the committee he sits on, Health,
Education and Welfare.
   ``I talked to most of the members of the committee and it was
clear to me that we had a majority to pass that,'' Kennedy said. ``I
was told to go speak to the leadership, and I went to speak to
(Majority Leader) Tom Lamb and he said, `Well, we have to look into
this more,' and it was tabled.
   ``And I asked around, `what did this mean?' and people said,
`Well, that's tantamount to letting a bill die quietly.' ''
   The committee's chairman, Democrat Frank J. Fiorenzano, said
Kennedy's family background should have prepared him for his
legislative losses.
   ``Maybe he's disappointed that things didn't move as fast as he
wanted them to, but he shouldn't have been taken aback,'' Fiorenzano
said. ``I've submitted some pieces of legislation every year since
I've been elected and they still haven't been passed.''
   Kennedy said his father's life in the U.S. Senate was nothing
like the routine of the Rhode Island Statehouse.
   ``My father ... has had to come to compromise, he's had to work
on things with other colleagues and he's had to agree and
disagree,'' Kennedy said. ``That's the way the legislative process
is supposed to work, and that can still work without it being (a
system) where the shots are called without any compromise or
agreement.''
   The Rev. H. Philip West Jr., director of the Rhode Island chapter
of Common Cause, a legislative watchdog group, agreed that power is
highly centralized in the state house. ``So much seems to happen
here by the decision from the speaker's office,'' he said.
   Kennedy said he plans to seek re-election despite his frustration
with the system, and already is busy deflecting attacks from
Republicans. The GOP did not run anyone against him last year but
since then has criticized Kennedy repeatedly for raising thousands
of dollars from out-of-state sources.
   `Where I receive my contributions has no bearing whatsoever on my
voting. I thought it was offensive that they implied that people in
this neighborhood had their votes for sale,'' he said. ``After a
certain point, the amount of money you spend in a local race is
ineffective because people have to meet you.''
   House leaders said Kennedy has been as effective as any freshman
legislator and could have a bright future if he remains in the House.
   Speaker Joseph DeAngelis said he never had asked for Kennedy's
vote on any particular bill, but, ``On those issues that were party
issues, he has always been a Democrat.''
   Fiorenzano praised Kennedy's devotion to the job.
   ``Everyone, when you first get up there, thinks they're going to
change the world,'' Fiorenzano said. ``Then you learn not everyone
shares your view and you have to work with other people to reach
compromises on your issues.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
