<FIRST>u i AM-Iran-Iraq     09-17 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Iraq,0560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran Threatens Force if Iraq Does Not Give Up Land</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian President Hashemi Rafsanjani said
Sunday that if Iraq does not relinquish Iranian territory it seized
in the last days of the Persian Gulf war, his country ``will make it
retreat by force.''
   It was the toughest statement made by an Iranian leader since a
cease-fire in the eight-year war took effect Aug. 20, 1988.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in
Nicosia, quoted Rafsanjani as telling commanders of Iran's
Revolutionary Guards: ``We have no territorial ambitions, but we
will not cede one inch of our Islamic land.''
   Rafsanjani did not give Iraq a deadline but said, ``We will be
patient as far as possible.'' His comments to commanders of the
paramilitary Revolutionary Guards were carried by the official
Islamic Republic News Agency in a report monitored in Nicosia.
   ``It will be very easy for us to regain our land,'' said
Rafsanjani, who was elected July 28. He made clear Iran will not
make any concessions to break a deadlock in peace talks that began
more than a year ago.
   The Iranians insist there can be no advance in the talks until
the Iraqis withdraw from Iranian soil.
   Iran claims the Iraqis hold 1,028 square miles of Iranian border
territory. U.N. observers say the Iraqis hold 386 square miles.
   The land was captured in a series of Iraqi offensives shortly
before the cease-fire took effect.
   Those military setbacks were a key factor in forcing Tehran to
accept the U.N. cease-fire resolution.
   ``Iran is not seeking any illogical concession from Iraq, just as
it will not make any concessions to the enemy, even if the present
situation lasts 10 years,'' Rafsanjani said at the Revolutionary
Guards' commanders annual conference in Tehran.
   ``If one day we become certain that the enemy is not willing to
return our land, we will make it retreat by force,'' he declared.
   Rafsanjani said Iran has no desire to resume the war, which by
Western military estimates killed more than 1 million people. Iran
was believed to have suffered losses three times as heavy as Iraq.
   In addition to the land issue, the peace talks are stalled over
disagreements concerning the Shatt-al-Arab waterway, the southern
boundary between the nations.
   Iraq is demanding that Iran allow the waterway _ Iraq's main
outlet to the Persian Gulf _ to be dredged and reopened. Iran
refuses.
   In addition, Iraq does not recognize a 1975 treaty that drew the
Iran-Iraq border down the center of the waterway. Before that
treaty, the border ran down the Iranian bank of the Shatt-al-Arab.
Iran says the 1975 treaty is valid.
   Rafsanjani said Iran will not back down on the Shatt-al-Arab.
   ``We will repel the enemy to the borders defined in the 1975
accord,'' he said.
   Before Rafsanjani spoke, Iran's spiritual leader, Ayatollah Ali
Khamenei, told commanders their forces and the regular army must be
in a state of constant combat readiness.
   But he noted: ``We are determined to achieve peace within the
framework of the U.N. Security Council resolution and we will never
initiate a step to weaken it.''
   The last session of peace talks was held in April under U.N.
auspices.
</TEXT>
