<FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-89 1254EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Babylon     09-17 0641</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Babylon,0659</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebuilt Babylon to Harken Back to Fabled Past</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALAH HASRAWI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BABYLON, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Songs written 6,000 years ago and deciphered
from stone tablets will waft through this fabled city on Friday as
Babylon relives the ancient days when it was the center of
civilization.
   Tens of thousands of people are expected at the huge cultural
extravaganza planned in Babylon, which is about 55 miles south of
Baghdad.
   The city was rebuilt by President Saddam Hussein at a cost of
about $100 million in an ambitious program to revive the splendors
of the past and to build a tourist industry folowing the eight-year
Persian Gulf war.
   For two weeks, Babylon's reconstructed palaces and temples will
echo with music, opera, dance and drama performed by troupes from
the United States, the Soviet Union, Japan and 35 other countries.
   The focuses of the festival will be the 2,500-seat Greek
amphitheater, built in the 4th Century B.C. by Alexander the Great,
who died in Babylon; and the crown hall in the Palace of
Nebuchadnezzar II, who ruled in the 6th century B.C.
   ``Babylon was the center of the world's civilization, arts and
culture and it is right that it regain that fame again,'' said Munir
Bashir, chief director of the festival.
   The first festival was held here in 1987, when Iran and Iraq were
at war. Last year's festival was held just a month after the
hostilities ceased under a U.N.-brokered truce.
   An estimated 100,000 people flocked to Babylon for last year's
festival, which featured artists from 24 countries, including
Brazilian guitarist Maria Liva Sao Marcos, the American Jeff Gardner
Jazz Quartet, the Leningrad Ballet and the Glamos Folk Group from
Norway.
   Only a handful of Europeans and Americans attended. But the
Iraqis expect more this year.
   ``Now that the war's over, we expect many more people,'' Bashir
said.
   A highlight, he said, will be an Iraqi troupe's presentation of
songs, dance and music based on ancient Babylonian music.
   The ancient music was played primarily on harps, some of which
have been found in the ruins of the city on the banks of the
Euphrates River.
   Bashir and other Iraqi researchers spent months unraveling the
notations on stone tablets to reproduce the primitive tunes, which
will be performed in public for the first time in millenia.
   Bashir, 59, is director of music at the Ministry of Information
and Culture and is the world's most renowned virtuoso of the oud, an
Arabic stringed instrument that was the forebear of the lute.
   The Iraqis claim that the ancient land known as Mesopotamia, or
``land between the rivers'' _ the Euphrates and Tigris _ was the
``cradle of civilization.'' It is also the reputed site of the
Garden of Eden.
   The Babylonians ruled an empire that flourished as a cultural,
religious and commercial center for hundreds of years. The legal and
social codes they developed were the first to provide for individual
and family rights and have influenced modern legal systems.
   Thousands of Iraqi, Sudanese and Egyptian laborers have toiled in
the blistering heat for the last few years to rebuild the
54,000-square foot Palace of Nebuchadnezzar, the Temples of
Nabashkhari and Ninmakh, the Processional Way, Babylon's main
thoroughfare, and the Ishtar Gate, named after the Babylonians' main
goddess.
   Officials said an estimated 15 million bricks, baked as they were
in ancient times, were used to restore the city's monuments based on
archaeological evidence, cuneiform texts and the description of
historians of the day.
   In other attractions at the festival, the Soviet Union will send
an Azerbaijani dance troupe, the Joyce Trisslet dance troupe is
coming from the United States.
   The amphitheater this year has been equipped with
state-of-the-art technology, including three-dimensional projectors,
to transform the performances at the ancient site into what one
official called ``a journey through time.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
