<FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-89 1328EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-US-EastGerman     09-17 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-East German,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hungarian Ambassador Denies Kremlin Approved Opening Borders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Hungarian ambassador to the United States
on Sunday denied Western speculation that the Kremlin had given
prior approval to his government's decision to open its borders to
East Germans fleeing to the West.
   Ambassador Peter Varkonyi told a television interviewer that ``I
haven't got strict information on'' the decision, but that
``Hungarian decisions are made in Budapest,'' the Hungarian capital.
   ``Of course, there is a diplomatic way of consultation and
information, but the decision was taken in Budapest,'' Varkonyi said
on the ABC-TV program, ``This Week with David Brinkley.''
   Asked whether the decision had been made ``without reference to
the Soviet Union,'' the ambassador replied, ``Without any reference
to the Soviet Union at all.''
   The Washington Post, in an article from Oslo, Norway, published
in its Sunday editions, quoted unidentified Western officials saying
that Hungary consulted with the Kremlin before allowing the East
Germans to leave.
   And a former senior U.S. government official said she believed
the Kremlin had approved the Hungarian decision in advance.
   Rozanne L. Ridgway, a former ambassador to East Germany and
Assistant Secretary of State for European Affairs, asked whether she
thought Moscow had given Hungary the green light, said: ``I do think
that is true.''
   The Hungarian ambassador to Washington said that although the
flight of an estimated 14,000 East Germans across Hungarian borders
to the West had drawn criticism from the East German leadership, his
government did not plan to close the frontier.
   ``To send them back against their will and without any provisions
that they would be immune to any punishment, and would have a legal
opportunity to emigrate, would have been not correct and we would
like to comply with our international obligations on human rights,''
he said.
   Multilateral agreements signed by Western and Soviet bloc nations
``explicitly say certain things about choice of emigration,'' and
nations that do sign but do not heed those pacts are in violation,
he said.
   ``If they are not ensuring a choice of emigration, it seems to be
that it isn't complying with the international agreements we have
signed,'' Varkonyi said.
   Two other guests on the ABC program, West German ambassador S.
Juergen Ruhfus and Theo Summer, editor of the newspaper Die Zeit of
Hamburg, predicted the East German government would be forced to
drop its resistance to the types of political and economic reform
underway in Hungary, Poland the Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
