<FIRST>r a AM-People     09-17 0690</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People,0719</SECOND>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer K.T. Oslin, who has two
big-selling country albums, was named female vocalist of the year in
1988 and has numerous awards to her credit, once hated country music.
   ``I loathed it,'' she said. ``Country music, at that time, was
all middle-aged men, singing about drinking and cheating on their
ever-loyal wives.''
   Ms. Oslin, 46, says her music still isn't pure country, but says
it's more country than anything.
   ``I think there's an audience of people out there that don't
listen to country music at all that would like my stuff,'' she said.
``I'd like to find them.''
   Ms. Oslin, who performed in Dallas on Saturday night, began her
career on the Broadway stage in a 1967 production of ``Hello,
Dolly!'' but made her mark on the country charts with the anthem
``80s Ladies.''
   The Academy of Country Music named her female vocalist of the
year last year and she garnered a Grammy award this year for her
hit, ``Hold Me.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exiled Greek King Constantine and his
Danish-born wife, Anne-Marie, had a royal celebration of their
silver wedding anniversary.
   The guest list of their weekend bash read like regal who's who:
King Juan Carlos of Spain, King Carl-Gustaf of Sweden, the Prince of
Wales and Queen Beatrix of Holland.
   In all, 300 relatives and friends gathered to celebrate the
pair's 25th wedding anniversary. The festivities started Saturday
with a gala dinner in the 16th century fortress of Kronborg, known
as Elsinore Castle in William Shakepeare's play Hamlet.
   Heavily armed police with dogs patrolled the grounds and the
rampart and frogmen searched the waters around the sand-stone
fortress.
   Also among the guests were Grand Duc Jean of Luxembourg and three
former titleholders: King Simeon of Bulgaria, King Michael of
Rumania and Crown Prince Alexander of Yugoslavia.
   Constantine and Anne-Marie went into exile in 1967 after an
abortive countercoup against a military junta that overthrew Premier
Panayiotis Canellopoulos the same year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vocalist Gail Nelson sang ``I Got Rhythm,'' and
she wasn't alone in being caught up with the beat as a sellout crowd
gathered to celebrate the Detroit Symphony Orchestra's official
return to Orchestra Hall.
   Nelson joined guest conductor Mitch Miller, dancer Gregory Hines,
two high school bands, clowns from the Detroit Fire Department and
other entertainers in the orchestra's homecoming show.
   Friday's event marked the symphony's permanent relocation in
Orchestra Hall after a half-century absence and an 18-year effort to
rescue the building from ruin.
   Orchestra Hall was built for the Detroit Symphony in 1919 for
about $1 million. But the orchestra fell on hard times during the
Depression and was evicted in 1939 after several years of missed
rent and tax payments.
   Paul Ganson, a Detroit Symphony bassoonist, helped found Save
Orchestra Hall in 1971 after hearing plans to destroy the building.
The organization bought the building and raised more than $10
million to finance repairs and restoration work.
   On Friday, Ganson proclaimed: ``Home at last! Home at last! Thank
God almighty, we're home at last!''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer Don Henley, the former Eagles band member on
tour to drum up interest for his third solo album, says he has a
hard time relating to most of today's pop music.
   ``I don't know if it's because I'm getting older or what, but a
lot of this new music seems incredibly moronic to me,'' said the
42-year-old musician. ``On the other hand, rock 'n' roll isn't
supposed to be too cerebral.''
   Henley, who performed in Dallas on Saturday, said he relates only
to his own music and that of Tom Petty.
   ``If you look at the other stuff that's in the Top 10,'' he said,
``it's me and Paula Abdul and New Kids On the Block and Milli
Vanilli and Prince's `Batman.' It's pretty grim up there.''
   But Henley, who grew up in the East Texas town of Linden, doesn't
dwell too much in the past as far as his concert selections are
concerned.
   ``We do three Eagles songs in each set. That's about enough,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
