<FIRST>u i AM-China     09-17 0614</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China,0632</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Steps Up Rhetoric Against Foreign Journalists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China stepped up its campaign against the Western
press Sunday, reprinting a 65-year-old commentary calling for the
expulsion of all foreign reporters.
   Also Sunday, Premier Li Peng told a Japanese delegation that the
government will not soon lift martial law in Beijing because
citizens seized many weapons from the army during the June crackdown
on pro-democracy protesters.
   The official Beijing Daily reprinted on its front page a 1924
essay by Li Dazhao, co-founder of the Chinese Communist Party,
saying China was the victim of ``journalistic invasion.''
   The article applauded the expulsion of a British reporter who
erroneously reported the death of Sun Yat-sen, the man regarded as
the father of modern China. Sun died in 1925.
   But Li Dazhao said expelling one reporter was not enough. ``The
Chinese government ... should expel all foreign reporters, who
spread rumors, make trouble and insult China,'' he said.
   The article was accompanied by another commentary saying the
article shows that foreign journalists have been spreading rumors in
China for decades.
   ``The `press freedoms' of imperialist countries haven't
progressed at all,'' it said.
   It said Li Dazhao's writings were reprinted to show that the
``rumor-mongering'' of Voice of America, the American
government-funded radio station, was not ``an accidental mistake.''
   Voice of America, regarded by its large Chinse audience as one of
the few independent sources of information available, has been
repeatedly attacked by the government for its reporting on the
democracy movement.
   China ordered seven reporters, including two from VOA, to leave
during the crisis in June which led to troops firing on
demonstrators, killing hundreds and perhaps thousands.
   A third commentary in Sunday's Economic Information criticized
leaders of the democracy movement for calling for freedom of the
press, saying they have an idealized view of Western freedoms.
   Official newspapers in May gave colorful, accurate coverage of
the pro-democracy protests, exhibiting a degree of journalistic
independence never before seen in China. But in the current
crackdown on dissent they have reverted to conveying the party line.
   Sunday's commentary claimed that press freedoms do not exist in
Western countries and that the American media are controlled by 50
powerful companies that ``not only hold the media organizations'
economic lifeblood but also directly intervene in (their) reporting
and editing policies.''
   It singled out political scientist Yan Jiaqi for ``beautifying
the press freedoms of Western countries'' and Shanghai's World
Economic Herald for ``showing unusual interest in political
questions.''
   Yan, an adviser to ousted party chief Zhao Ziyang, fled to the
West shortly after the June military attack. The Herald was
temporarily shut down and its editor, Qin Benli, was fired for
supporting the student-led movement.
   ``In socialist China ... to be a journalist of the party (means)
to be of one mind with the party,'' the article said.
   The commentaries Sunday follow a series of essays in recent weeks
on the role of journalism in China.
   Japanese sources said Premier Li told former Foreign Minister
Masayoshi Ito, who is heading a five-member parliamentary delegation
to China, that martial law must continue because hundreds of weapons
seized by citizens during the June 3-4 clash with the military have
yet to be retrieved.
   The premier, in his meeting with Japanese leaders, said life in
Beijing had returned to normal, but anti-government forces still
exist and the military was needed to assist police in maintaining
order, the Japanese sources reported.
   The sources said Ito urged Li to lift martial law soon. He also
said that although Japan did not want to interfere in China's
internal affairs, China should realize that the military suppression
of the protesters had hurt China's international image.
</TEXT>
