<FIRST>r w AM-CongressRdp     09-17 0648</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress Rdp,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Capitol Hill Debate on Drug War Freezes Spending Bills</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republicans may propose a new strategy Monday
to pay for the war on drugs as Congress continues its debate on
President Bush's plan to fight narcotics trafficking, Senate
Minority Leader Bob Dole said Sunday.
   With two weeks before the start of a new fiscal year, Congress is
scrambling to pass a dozen money bills needed to keep the government
running, but is stymied over how to wage and finance the war on
drugs.
   The money measures are stacked up in the Senate like planes over
a busy airport as negotiators try to work out the politically
charged drug issue, with both Democrats and Republicans angling to
show they care more than the other side about the narcotics scourge.
   ``We have fundamentally different objectives and goals,'' said
Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., chairman of the Senate Judiciary
Committee. He said Democrats will be content only if the growth in
the number of cocaine addicts is reversed, drug treatment is
provided for all who want it and drug education is extended to
nearly every school child in the country.
   There are ``glaring deficiencies'' in Bush's plan, particularly
in those areas, Biden said. And signaling his party's intention to
make drugs a political battleground, he promised ``a much broader
Democratic strategy'' to be elucidated in the weeks and months ahead.
   Republicans claimed the issue as their top priority as well and
said Bush had fulfilled his mandate by proposing an ambitious and
comprehensive anti-drug package.
   Dole said Sunday on NBC's ``Meet the Press'' that ``I don't think
we find any problem in the president's package.''
   Bush himself said he remains flexible about how to pay for the
initiative, but added: ``I strongly believe that we must retain the
integrated elements of this drug strategy, which took more than six
months to develop.''
   The president proposed increasing spending by $1.5 billion over
what he had asked in his initial fiscal 1990 budget request, with
the heaviest emphasis on law enforcement and prosecution. He sought
to pay for the program by reducing spending on other domestic
programs.
   Senate Appropriations Committee Chairman Robert Byrd, D-W.Va.,
then upped the ante by proposing an additional $2.2 billion in
spending, to be paid for with an across-the-board spending cut of
about half a percent. Byrd's emphasis was on treatment and education.
   Senate negotiators for the two sides _ nine Democrats and nine
Republicans _ were to meet again late Monday to see whether
agreement could be reached on a drug-fighting plan and a way to pay
for it. But until such a package could be worked out, the spending
bills that will include any payment scheme were effectively frozen
in place.
   ``It'll be a critical meeting,'' Dole said. ``We may make a
counter offer at that time _ Republican.''
   Dole rejected Byrd's proposal and said ``we ought to look at more
than across-the-board cuts. We ought to look at ... other ways to
find the money.''
   As the Senate wrangled over drugs, the House Democratic
leadership was seeking to formulate an alternative to the capital
gains tax cut approved last week by the Ways and Means Committee.
   The tax-writing panel handed Bush a major victory on the issue,
but Democrats want to head it off on the House floor by offering an
alternative tax package that would be more philosophically in tune
with their theme of fighting for the middle class _ possibly
including a new tax break for individual retirement accounts.
   The House floor agenda for the week included consideration of a
$270 million bill to provide for increased security and weapons
detection systems at airports, and legislation that would regulate
shipping to prevent catastrophic accidents such as the Alaskan oil
spill and make those involved in oil transportation pay the full
costs of cleanup.
</TEXT>
