<FIRST>r i AM-SouthAfrica     09-17 0554</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa,0570</SECOND>
<HEAD>De Klerk Wins Praise, But The Honeymoon Likely to be Brief</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect F.W. de Klerk
has won praise for allowing huge anti-apartheid marches, but
political analysts said Sunday the honeymoon will be brief unless he
quickly brings reforms.
   In a major policy shift, de Klerk said Tuesday that police will
not disrupt peaceful demonstrations, previously banned or forcefully
dispersed.
   A day later, 20,000 activists in Cape Town staged the country's
largest legal demonstration, followed by similar protests Friday in
Johannesburg and Pretoria.
   ``Nice going, F.W. _ but what's next?'' the Sunday Star of
Johannesburg asked in an editorial. ``A few protest marches do not
alter the fundamental (apartheid) system which governs our lives .
.. The window of opportunity (for reform) is open but it will not
remain so for long.''
   De Klerk, to be sworn into office Wednesday, says he wants to
give the 28-million voteless black majority a limited role within
five years in the national government, now dominated by leaders of
South Africa's 5 million whites.
   On Saturday, de Klerk named Gerrit Viljoen, the former minister
of black education, to spearhead government efforts to negotiate a
new constitution with blacks.
   Viljoen, who has a doctorate in literature, is a bookish,
soft-spoken, political moderate closely allied with de Klerk.
   Black leaders are skeptical of de Klerk's promises, and bringing
them to the negotiating table will not be easy. They refuse to have
talks with the government, saying it first must end the 3-year-old
state of emergency, release political prisoners such as Nelson
Mandela and legalize the guerrilla-backed African National Congress
and other banned organizations.
   Activists say they will analyze de Klerk's offer at a major Oct.
7 conference in Johannesburg on strategy to end South Africa's
apartheid system of legal race discrimination.
   ``We will have an opportunity ... to look at Mr. de Klerk's
promises and his ability to fulfill them,'' anti-apartheid leader
the Rev. Allan Boesak said Saturday.
   Meanwhile, activists will pursue a 6-week-old nationwide campaign
of defiance that has targeted segregated schools, hospitals,
beaches, buses and other facilities.
   A march through downtown Durban is scheduled Friday, and
additional beach protests are set for the end of September.
   De Klerk's calls for reform remain vague and likely will draw
fire from activists and conservatives when he begins to spell out
changes.
   ``He has done little more than commit himself to the political
equivalents of apple pie and mother's love _ negotiated solutions
and a peaceful, prosperous society,'' wrote Lester Venter, political
columnist for the Sunday Times, the country's largest paper. ``The
content of the man's political vision ... is not yet clear.''
   The extreme-right Conservative Party, which opposes all
concessions to blacks, has harshly attacked de Klerk for authorizing
the demonstrations.
   ``A knife has been thrust in the back of the upholders of law and
order,'' said Conservative spokesman Moolman Mentz.
   Several local newspapers reported de Klerk approved the protests
despite opposition from security officials, who seldom were
overruled by de Klerk's retiring predecessor, P.W. Botha.
   De Klerk calls for an end to discrimination, but insists he will
preserve segregated schools and neighborhoods for whites who want
them.
   He also has made clear he will not accept a one-man, one-vote
political system, or black majority rule.
</TEXT>
