<FIRST>r w AM-Congress-Fighters     09-17 0583</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Fighters,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fight to Save ``Top Gun'' Tomcat Hinges on Fate of New Fighter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's decision earlier this year to
cancel the Navy's F-14D jet fighter that achieved fame in the movie
``Top Gun'' touched off a major campaign in Congress to save the
carrier aircraft.
   The lobbying paid off last month when the House approved a bill
that restored $1 billion for 24 planes over the next two years.
   The Senate, in its defense bill, had endorsed the president's
plan to kill the Tomcat fighter.
   As members of the House and Senate get down to fashioning a final
version of the defense bill during the coming week, congressional
backers of the F-14D are taking heart in the woes of another
aircraft _ the Advanced Tactical Fighter.
   The two prototypes of the plane _ one for the Navy and one for
the Air Force _ will not share a common design, forcing the Defense
Department to pay for two separate fighter plane programs, according
to recent reports.
   Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., chairman of the Armed Services Committee,
said at a hearing earlier this month that development of the
next-generation aircraft, which is intended to succeed the Air
Force's F-15 and the Navy's F-14D, has slipped six months.
   The problems prompted the House, in its appropriations bill, to
eliminate the $1.1 billion for the Air Force's fighter and $65
million for the Navy's version in the fiscal 1990 budget.
   ``The (House Appropriations) committee is not convinced ... that
the ATF program as currently structured will meet the requirement
with a mission and cost effective solution,'' the panel said in its
report accompanying the spending bill.
   Specifically, the committee complained that the Air Force
predicts the ATF will be built at a rate of 72 per year, yet it has
been unable ``to achieve such a sustained rate for the F-15 which by
any measure is a much cheaper aircraft.''
   The panel also noted that in the last six months, the cost of
research and development of the program has increased by $900
million, to $13.5 billion.
   With the Air Force planning to buy 750 advanced tactical fighters
at a total cost of about $64 billion and the Navy planning to
replace the F-14D with the ATF, the price could exceed the $70
billion for the B-2 stealth bomber program.
   That bat-winged aircraft is considered the most expensive in
history.
   Lawmakers indicated last week that although the problems of the
advanced tactical fighter have raised concerns on Capitol Hill, and
may help the F-14D campaign, the House-Senate conferees likely will
restore much of the money for the radar-evading fighter.
   The action by the House was the proverbial shot across the bow,
members said.
   ``It was a strong message to the administration and the Air
Force,'' said Rep. Norman Dicks, D-Wash., a member of the House
Appropriations subcommittee on defense.
   Two groups are building prototypes of the plane. Northrop and
McDonnell Douglas are building the design known as YF-23 while
Lockheed, Boeing and General Dynamics are constructing YF-22. The
prototypes are scheduled to fly next year with the contract to be
awarded in January 1991.
   Ideally, the ATF will replace the F-14D, manufactured by Grumman
Corp., of New York, without a void in the Navy's line of carrier
fighters.
   ``We hope to sequence in the ATF and not have a gap,'' said Rep.
Joseph M. McDade of Pennsylvania, ranking Republican on the
Appropriations defense subcommittee.
</TEXT>
