<DOCNO> AP890917-0034 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-89 1450EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p AM-SeattleMayor     09-17 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Seattle Mayor,0600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seattle Mayoral Election Long on Candidates, Short on Issues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM KLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five political veterans are leading eight others
in the primary race for mayor of Seattle, often touted as one of the
nation's most liveable cities but facing problems with crime,
desegregation and traffic.
   The large field without any clear front-runner contributed to a
largely ho-hum race for Tuesday's primary, said Deputy Mayor Charles
Stafford, an 18-year City Hall veteran.
   The top two finishers in the primary for the non-partisan office
meet in a runoff Nov. 7. There are no statewide candidates on the
ballot this year, but an unusual number of cities across Washington
state are selecting successors to outgoing mayors.
   Mayor Charles Royer is leaving after an unprecedented three
four-year terms to become director of the Institute of Politics at
the John F. Kennedy School of Government at Harvard University.
   Although there is no overwhelming favorite, City Councilman Norm
Rice, who is seeking to become Seattle's first black mayor, is
generally seen as the likely top vote-getter. Randy Revelle, a
former city councilman and county executive, and Doug Jewett, the
city attorney, are considered best bets for the No. 2 runoff spot.
Also given a shot are council members Dolores Sibonga and Jim Street.
   Judging partly by voter turnout in 1985, when Royer defeated Rice
by a more than 5-to-3 margin, Bob Bruce of the King County Records
and Elections Division has predicted about 28 percent of the city's
approximately 300,000 registered voters will cast ballots.
   In recent years Seattle consistently has been picked as one of
the country's best places to live, do business and raise children.
Its maritime environment, mountain views and booming economy rank
high in magazine surveys.
   ``I don't want to sound too self-serving, but it's kind of hard
to beat up on the government,'' said Royer, the incumbent. ``We've
done a good job. The city is in terrific financial shape.''
   However, at the same time burglary rates are skyrocketing, there
is debate over school desegregation, and traffic congestion rivals
that of Los Angeles.
   The leading mayoral candidates differ less on these issues than
on terms of experience, leadership and style.
   ``I think it is very difficult to define any big differences in
terms of the issues,'' said Rice.
   ``There is a strong overlap among all of us in terms of a
progressive, liberal approach to social services, housing and these
sorts of issues,'' said Street.
   Jewett is the only major candidate who supports an initiative to
end mandatory busing for school desegregation, partly by diverting
some $4 million a year in city tax revenues to finance projects
designed to attract a racial balance by voluntary school
registration.
   Also on the ballot are Mountaineers Club president Carsten Lien
and advertising man David Stern, credited with creating the smiling
yellow ``happy face.'' The face figured in a 1967 ad campaign for a
local bank, and Stern's using it now in his own campaign.
   For whose who call the vacantly smiling circle superficial, Stern
counters: ``The Happy Face is not frivolous. It's a symbol of my
optimism, and that's important. We need optimism. I'm very
optimistic about this city.''
   Candidates with almost no visible campaign organizations are Herb
Gandy, a Boeing Co. photographer; Bob Hegamin, a retired City Light
engineer; Pete Mitchell, a Ballard business operator; Robbie Scherr,
a Socialist Workers Party activist; Constance Paulson, a Navy
veteran; and Bob Willmott, founder of the free food and shelter
group Strand Helpers.
</TEXT>
