<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Armenia     09-17 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Armenia,0541</SECOND>
<HEAD>Armenia, Faced With Economic ``Blockade,'' Plans Appeal to Kremlin</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers in Armenia, under virtual economic
blockade from neighboring Azerbaijan, met in emergency session
Sunday to ask the Kremlin for help in restoring deliveries of food
and fuel, activists said.
   On Saturday, the legislature of Azerbaijan again laid claim to
Nagorno-Karabakh, a hilly region mostly populated by Armenians that
has been the focus of a bloody territorial conflict between the two
Soviet republics for the 18 months.
   Speaking by telephone from Yerevan, Armenia's capital, an editor
at the official Armenpress news agency said that during the past 14
days, not a single freight car with cargo has arrived in Armenia
over rail routes originating in Azerbaijan.
   The editor, who was cut off before he could give his name, said
5,000 freight cars were also overdue in the area of Armenia that was
devastated by an earthquake in December. The earthquake killed
25,000 people and left hundreds of thousands homeless.
   Armenian activist Rafael Popoyan said the republic's Communist
Party chief, Suren Arutyunyan, told Armenia's legislature at the
emergency session that ``during the past two months Armenia has not
been receiving food, construction materials or food due to the
blockade.''
   A resolution submitted for the Armenian Supreme Soviet's
consideration denounces the blockade as ``an act of aggression'' and
demands the national Moscow-based legislature take urgent measures
to restore shipments to Armenia and Nagorno-Karabakh within 24
hours, Popoyan said.
   The special session of the Armenian legislature will also
consider the situation in Nagorno-Karabakh, which was part of mostly
Moslem Azerbaijan for more than 65 years despite its largely
Armenian and Christian population.
   More than 100 people have died in ethnic bloodshed since Armenia
and Azerbaijan began fighting over the district in February 1988. In
an attempt to end the killing, the Kremlin placed the district under
its direct control in February.
   Azerbaijan's parliament reaserted its right to rule
Nagorno-Karabakh on Saturday, calling the district an integral part
of the republic and noting that the Soviet Constitution classifies
it as such.
   The intractable quarrel will be one of the thorniest problems
faced by the Soviet Communist Party leadership when it meets Tuesday
in Moscow to try to redefine policy towards the country's more than
130 ethnic groups and seek solutions to ethnic conflicts.
   Soviet press accounts have commonly blamed the cutoff in freight
shipments to Armenia on striking Azerbaijani railway workers. But
the scope of the blockade indicates officials in Azerbaijan either
are taking an active part in it or are doing little to end it.
   State-run Radio Moscow reported Sunday that the single rail
station in Nagorno-Karabakh, in the administrative center of
Stepanakert, has been out of operation for 10 days because trains
bound there are halted 13 miles away in the Azerbaijan city of Agdam.
   By road, ``convoys with fuel and food bound for Nagorno-Karabakh
are stopped in the adjoining (Azerbaijani) areas,'' the radio added.
   For lack of fuel, farm work in the district has stopped, Radio
Moscow said. ``No fuel is available for private cars. Even
ambulances, emergency service vehicles and police cars receive
rationed fuel supplies,'' it said.
</TEXT>
