<FIRST>r i AM-Angola     09-17 0544</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Angola,0565</SECOND>
<HEAD>Angolan Rebel Leader Says Peace Talks Likely To Fail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angolan guerrilla leader Jonas
Savimbi says Zairean President Mobutu Sese Seko's attempt to
negotiate an end to the civil war in his country is likely to fail
and another mediator should be found.
   Savimbi's remarks Saturday night appeared to rule out any hope
that an African summit Monday in Kinshasa, the Zairean capital,
would reinstate a truce in Angola's 14-year-old civil war.
   ``I think Mobutu is not the only one who can make the
reconciliation happen. ... I don't see how he is going to continue.
I think he is going to fail,'' Savimbi told reporters.
   Without naming anyone, Savimbi also said, ``time will prove that
somebody was telling lies to one of the sides.''
   At issue are claims that Savimbi agreed to go into exile and
permit the integration if his guerrilla forces into the Angolan
army. Savimbi repeatedly has denied agreeing to either condition.
   His National Union for the Total Independence of Angola wants to
contest elections to win a share in a government which, with Cuban
and Soviet aid, fought its way to power when Portuguese colonizers
hastily withdrew from the southern African nation in 1975.
   The U.S. State Department released a statement Sunday saying it
``strongly supports (the guerrillas) and its goals of national
reconciliation followed by free and fair elections.
   ``The United States does not accept the concept of `exile,
amnesty or integration,''' it said.
   Savimbi said he will not attend the Kinshasa summit, despite
pressure from his backers in Washington, unless Mobutu disassociates
himself from efforts to force him into exile.
   The Angolan rebels get $15 million a year from the United States,
funneled through Zaire. Mobutu also has given the guerrilla leader
substantial assistance.
   But on Saturday, Savimbi accused Mobutu of siding with Angolan
President Jose Eduardo dos Santos.
   He said it would be possible for someone else to take over the
peace negotiations.
   ``We are for genuine reconciliation, for a lasting peace. If
anyone will negotiate this ... We are for him,'' said Savimbi.
   He was in Abidjan for a meeting with Ivorian President Felix
Houphouet-Boigny, whom African diplomats said he favored to take
over as mediator.
   Savimbi also said fighting had intensified in Angola in the last
two weeks with his guerrillas killing nearly 1,000 government troops
while losing 300 men. Officials of the Luanda government also have
reported increased fighting.
   Under an agreement mediated by Mobutu, a cease-fire began June
24. Fighting quickly resumed with dos Santos accusing the rebels of
widespread violations.
   Savimbi acknowledged some attacks, saying it was difficult to
communicate with thousands of irregulars spread across the country,
but also charged dos Santos with launching a major offensive.
   Savimbi added that reports he had accepted money to go into exile
had angered some of his supporters and provoked them to launch
attacks despite the cease-fire. Several African heads of state have
said Mobutu told them Savimbi had agreed to go into exile.
   The guerrilla leader said his troops have turned back an
offensive by 10,000 government soldiers without help from South
Africa, whose troops would intervene before an agreement last year
for the withdrawal of Cuban forces from Angola in return for
Namibian independence.
</TEXT>
