<FIRST>r w AM-AID-Hugo     09-17 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AID-Hugo,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Sending AID Team to Caribbean</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Agency for International Development
announced Sunday it had sent a team to the Caribbean to determine
whether emergency relief will be needed to cope with damage from
Hurricane Hugo.
   A team of two people was on the Caribbean Island of Antigua and
another two people have been sent to Barbados, an AID official said.
   ``The team in Barbados is carrying with them a portable satellite
communications unit, which will enable them to relay disaster relief
information and emergency needs from the disaster site back to'' the
Office of U.S. Foreign Disaster Assistance, AID announced in a news
release.
   ``At the present time, no emergency relief aid has been requested
by the affected islands,'' the announcement said.
   An AID worker, Arthur Feller, said reports from Antigua indicated
that by Sunday afternoon the storm had caused little damage.
   ``In the last conversation we had with our people in Antigua,
they said there was a lot of wind and a lot of rain, but no one was
hurt,'' said Feller.
   Asked whether AID planned to send food or other relief there,
Feller said, ``It is not clear that it is needed. If it is needed,
we can move very fast.''
   According to dispatches from the Caribbean, Hugo hit the resort
islands with 140 mph winds Sunday, tearing off roofs, knocking out
communications and reportedly leaving 3,000 people homeless.
   The region's most powerful storm in a decade then swept toward
the U.S. Virgin Islands and Puerto Rico. Both governments mobilized
the National Guard, and residents rushed for last-minute supplies
and taped and boarded windows.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
