<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--WellAccident     09-17 0178</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Well Accident,0180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Workers, EMT Killed by Methane Gas in Well</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DECATUR, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pocket of methane gas killed a man
cleaning a well, then killed two men who were tryint ot rescue him,
authorities said.
   Jerry Buckner, 31, and Gary Harden, 26, both of Calhoun, were
clearing land Saturday to make room for a trailer in this community
about 50 miles northeast of Chattanooga, and Buckner climbed into
the well to clear it, said Jim Mullins, a sheriff's dispatcher.
   Buckner was overcome by methane and died almost immediately,
police said. Harden ran to call rescuers, then returned, entered the
well and also was overcome by the gas.
   David McCullum, 27, an emergency medical technician with a county
rescue squad, entered the well without an airpack and also was
overcome, Mullins said. McCullum was pronounced dead on arrival at a
hospital.
   Methane gas can be formed by sewage, fertilizer and other
products, but ``how that exact pocket got there, I don't know,''
said Blake Bowers, an operations officer with the Tennessee
Emergency Management Agency.
</TEXT>
