<FIRST>u i AM-Afghanistan 1stLd-Writethru a0677 09-17 0729</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0677,0753</SECOND>
<HEAD>Afghan President Criticizes U.S. Meeting with Ex-King</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with Najib criticizing Washington;
pickup graf 7 pvs `But the....' SUBS graf 22 pvs `But another...' with
one graf to CORRECT `another spokesman' to `a spokesman... Edits throughout
and deletyes last two grafs to trim.</HEAD>
<HEAD>PRECEDE Islamabad</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MACFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Najib said Sunday that U.S.
officials are trying to bolster their aid to anti-communist rebels
by meeting with deposed Afghan King Zahir Shah in Italy.
   Radical Afghan guerrillas with bases in Pakistan threatened to
assassinate the former monarch if he tries to return and head a
postwar government in Kabul.
   The warring sides in Afghan's civil war commented after reports
that an envoy of the United States met with the exiled king in Rome.
Zahir Shah has lived in Italy since his nephew seized power in a
1973 coup.
   In his remarks, Najib said U.S. talks with Zahir Shah were an
attempt ``to bring fresh breath to the abortive military policy of
the U.S. government.'' He did not elaborate.
   However, the president also suggested Zahir Shah could have a
role in a settlement.
   ``We have proposed that all forces within and outside the
country, including Zahir Shah, take part in national
reconciliation,'' Najib said.
   Afghanistan's ruling Marxists and their Soviet backers have
previously said the king could serve as compromise solution to head
a transitional government.
   But hard-line rebels in Islamabad, Pakistan, warned Zahir Shah to
stay away from his homeland.
   ``He takes a very grave risk of being shot,'' said Nawab Salim,
spokesman for the Hezb-i-Islami party run by anti-American Gulbaddin
Hekmatyar. ``The mujahedeen (holy warriors) will not let Zahir Shah
come to Afghanistan.''
   After more than six months of trying to forge unity within the
fractious guerrilla coalition, Washington reportedly is considering
alternatives, including the former monarch.
   But the rebels, who have received millions of U.S. dollars in
military and humanitarian aid during their decade-long war with
successive communist governments, are bitterly divided over a
possible role for the 74-year-old king.
   Abdul Rahim, a spokesman for the guerrillas' government-in-exile,
said a royal return is tantamount to a rebel defeat. ``It would mean
the mujahedeen and the people of Afghanistan are defeated,'' said
Rahim.
   Royalists among the rebels, most notably Syed Gailani's National
Islamic Front of Afghanistan, say the king is the only Afghan able
to rally warring factions.
   Asim Nasser-Zia, a spokesman for Gailani's group, predicted Zahir
Shah will fly to Kabul from Rome in January or February and retire
after convening a traditional Afghan council to oversee general
elections.
   This could happen only after Najib was out of Kabul, he said.
   Pakistan's army chief of staff, Gen. Mirza Aslam Beg, said Sunday
the Kremlin appears willing to abandon Najib.
   In a briefing for reporters, Beg said Armand Hammer, U.S. oil
magnate and confidante of Moscow's powerbrokers, ``indicated the
Soviets may drop Najib.''
   He recommended the Afghan resistance negotiate with remaining
leaders of the Afghan Communist groups after Najib is removed.
   Talks with the ruling communists represent a radical departure
from Pakistan's earlier policies and is rejected by all rebels,
regardless of political leanings. The rebels have their headquarters
in Pakistan, which also shelters more than 3 million Afghan refugees.
   Salim charged Zahir Shah's possible return is a compromise being
considered by Washington and Moscow because the superpowers are
anxious to extricate themselves from the Afghan war.
   The United States fears a ``so-called fundamentalist''
government, said Salim, whose organization is one of Washington's
greatest critics but also is one of the major benefactors of U.S.
largesse.
   ``The United States is trying to impose him (Zahir Shah) on the
people of Afghanistan,'' said Salim, calling the monarch a
``traitor.''
   The king's greatest crime, according to critics, was to keep
silent during the war, particularly after 1979 when Moscow sent more
than 110,000 soldiers into Afghanistan.
   ``He never cared about the jihad (holy war),'' said Rahim. ``He
never participated practically.''
   The Kremlin withdrew its last troops from Afghanistan on Feb. 15
under a U.N.-brokered accord. Many observers expected the move to
lead to a guerrilla victory, but the divided resistance has not
captured any major towns since the Soviet pullout.
   But a spokesman for the Jamiat-i-Islami guerrilla faction, Omar
Sherdul, said 400 government soldiers surrendered to rebels in
western Herat province.
</TEXT>
