<FIRST>r a AM-DressCode     09-17 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dress Code,0485</SECOND>
<HEAD>Priest to Maintain Dress Code Policy Despite Archbishop's Request</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES HANNAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAYTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Roman Catholic priest said Sunday he would
continue enforcing a dress code at his church despite orders from
his archbishop that he stop refusing Holy Communion to people he
considers inappropriately dressed.
   The Rev. Roger Griese has barred shorts and mini-skirts from
Sacred Heart Church and has turned away from Communion people he
considers immodestly dressed.
   ``I do not refuse the Sacrament ... solely on the grounds of
inappropriate dress, but rather on the unworthy motive of
confrontation and attack which the wearers of inappropriate dress
insist on wearing, even after several warnings,'' Griese said. ``And
this, in simple conscience, I cannot change.''
   Griese told his congregation that Daniel Pilarczyk, the
archbishop of Cincinnati, has threatened him with suspension and
loss of his pastorate.
   ``He threatens me with removal,'' Griese said. ``Well, we'll see.
He doesn't have the right to do that when a person is innocent and
has done no wrong.
   ``If I'm going to be insulted by my own authorities, by my own
mission and staff, I have the right to make an appeal to Rome. And I
won't have any hesitancy about doing that,'' he said.
   Griese read a letter from Pilarczyk to the congregation at the
end of Sunday's Mass.
   In the letter, Pilarczyk told Griese that he too believes people
should come to church appropriately dressed. He said he also
believes it is proper for priests to remind churchgoers of the
respect owed to the church.
   ``At the same time, I do not believe that guidelines for dress
can and should be enforced by refusing the Sacraments to people,''
wrote Pilarczyk.
   ``I have indicated this to you and pointed out that in the future
you may not refuse Holy Communion or absolution in the Sacrament of
Penance purely on the grounds of inappropriate dress.
   ``I suspect that you do not agree with this, but as an obedient
priest you have said that you will carry out my wishes,'' the letter
said.
   Griese accused Pilarczyk of ``letting down the bars'' and
rewarding confronters by chastising a loyal priest who is simply
upholding reverence for the church.
   ``I shall not have that on my conscience,'' Griese said. ``And no
man has the authority or power to force another man's conscience.''
   The 73-year-old Griese said the controversy has caused him to
lose sleep and miss meals.
   ``(But) I'm at peace with God as to what I've done and how I've
done it,'' he said. ``And if that doesn't please the archbishop,
then I'm very sorry. But I have to follow my conscience.''
   Ray George, spokesman for the archdiocese, said Pilarczyk plans
to review Sunday's events at Sacred Heart and that no statement was
immediately planned.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
