<FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-89 1758EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-SriLanka     09-17 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0696</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Offers Cease-Fire if Extremists Agree to Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Sunday offered a
unilateral cease-fire to Sinhalese extremists if they join an
interparty peace conference that began last week.
   A statement by the president's office said ``there will be no
need for the armed forces to continue their ongoing security
operations'' if leaders of the People's Liberation Front attend the
conference.
   President Ranasinghe Premadasa called the meeting in an effort to
end ethnic strife that has taken 16,000 lives in six years. The
inaugural session Wednesday was attended by 21 of Sri Lanka's 27
recognized parties.
   The People's Liberation Front rejected Premadasa's invitation but
the president said he hoped it will attend later sessions. The
meetings are expected to continue through Oct. 12.
   The latest government truce offer came as military officials said
more than 300 people were killed last week in attacks by Liberation
Front extremists and reprisal raids by pro-government vigilante
groups.
   Vigilantes reportedly killed 150 people in repeated attacks on
three Kandy district villages on Friday and Saturday, apparently in
retaliation for the killing of three soldiers' relatives in Kandy by
Liberation Front gunmen.
   The government did not confirm the attacks on Menikhinna,
Kundasala and Aranagala, 50 miles northeast of Colombo.
   But a senior military official said the government had ordered a
major crackdown on vigilante groups.
   The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, also said 45
members of the armed forces were arrested on suspicion of
participating in vigilante groups.
   ``It is evident the current situation is being exploited by
unidentified armed groups for their own purposes. This has led to a
proliferation of weapons in our society. A positiive response by the
Front to the call for peace and normalcy will enable the
identification of these groups,'' the presidential statement said.
   A separate government statement Sunday said 16 bodies of young
Sinhalese men were found in southern towns with notes nearby
purportedly signed by the People's Liberation Red Army. The
Liberation Red Army is one of five known pro-governement groups.
   The government has denied it supports the Liberation Red Army or
other groups such as the Black Cats, Yellow Cats, Green Tigers and
the People's Revolutionary Army.
   Opposition lawmakers and human rights organizations claim the
government encourages such groups to intensify the crackdown on the
Liberation Front, an ultranationalist guerrilla group trying to
overthrow the government.
   A military offical said the death toll during the week passed
300. He said 100 buildings were also burned in seven days, the worst
week of violence in recent months.
   Independent sources said the death toll exceeded 350 and 250
buildings were burned.
   The government says more than 5,000 people have been killed in
the two-year campaign by the Liberation Front and blames the
extremists for most deaths. The Front says vigilantes are
responsible for many killings.
   Liberation Front rebels began their campaign of assassinations
and terrororist attacks to protest the government's peace overtures
to Tamil secessionists in the northeast.
   The Front said an accord two years ago that was sponsored by
India made too many concessions to the minority Tamils, who comprise
18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people.
   Liberation Front leaders also opposed the presence of Indian
peacekeeping soldiers, deployed in the northeast to supervise the
1987 accord. The largest Tamil group, Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam, reneged on the accord and began attacking the Indian troops.
At least 1,000 Indian soldiers have been killed in the fighting.
   The Tamil rebels are attending the peace conference.
   The Tamil secession, which began in 1983 with complaints of
discrimination in jobs and education by the Sinhalese-dominated
government, has claimed up to 10,000 Sri Lankan lives.
   Sinhalese, most of whom are Buddhists, make up 75 percent of the
population and control the government and the military. Tamils are
predominantly Buddhists.
   India became involved in the ethnic problems of its southeastern
neighbor because of the sympathies of its own 60 million Tamils to
the rebel cause.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
