<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-17 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parts Of West Get Moisture After Dry Summer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain fell across large areas of the West on Sunday, with some
areas getting their first moisture in months.
   In the Caribbean, Hurricane Hugo headed for the Virgin Islands
and Puerto Rico.
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered from the San Francisco
Bay area of California into southern Oregon, from western Montana
across Idaho, northern Nevada, northern Utah and western Wyoming,
and over central Arizona,
   In California, Santa Maria got its first measurable rainfall
since May, and since Saturday morning, San Diego had accumulated
0.08 of an inch of rain, the city's first since June 10.
   Showers and thunderstorms also were scattered from Florida across
the North Carolina coast, over western Pennsylvania and New York
state, and over northern Maine.
   Thunderstorms during the afternoon produced winds gusting to 55
mph with small hail at St. Petersburg, Fla.
   Miami warmed to a record 95 degrees, and on the northern Plains,
Dickinson, N.D., hit a record 92.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 46
degrees at Tahoe Valley, Calif., to 95 at Miami. Sunday's low for
the Lower 48 states was 26 at Gunnison, Colo.
   For Monday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
along the North Carolina and Georgia coasts. Showers were forecast
from Montana across western Wyoming, western Colorado, Utah, Idaho
and Nevada across the central coast of California.
   Highs in the 50s were predicted over the northern Rockies; in the
60s and 70s from New England across North Carolina, over the Ohio
Valley and the Great Lakes, from the remainder of Montana across
western Colorado and northern Arizona, from central Nevada across
Idaho over southwestern California and from central California
across Washington state; near 90 over Florida, the Gulf of Mexico
Coast and much of Texas; in the 90s through the desert Southwest;
and generally in the 80s over the remainder of the nation.
</TEXT>
