<FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-89 1914EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-TridentProtest     09-17 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trident Protest,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marchers Protest Shuttle Cargo, Navy Missile</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TITUSVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 40 peace activists carrying banners
and beating drums began a 200-mile march Sunday to protest the use
of nuclear power in the U.S. space program and by the military.
   The three-week march began at Cape Canaveral, where the Navy's
nuclear-armed Trident 2 missile system is tested, and will take
demonstrators to Kings Bay, Ga., where the missiles are to be
deployed aboard submarines.
   Members of the Florida Coalition for Peace and Justice plan to
join hundreds of other activists in a rally Oct. 8 outside the gates
of the Georgia submarine base.
   Coalition spokesman Bruce Gagnon said the activists will average
10 miles per day, stopping to distribute literature along the way.
   They are protesting both the Navy's Trident 2 program and NASA's
plans to launch a nuclear-powered spacecraft aboard the next space
shuttle.
   The spacecraft Galileo, waiting to be dispatched from Atlantis on
a six-year voyage to Jupiter, will get its power from two nuclear
generators containing 48 pounds of radioactive plutonium-238.
   The coalition has threatened to seek a court order and to
trespass on the launch pad if necessary to stop the flight, now set
for Oct. 12.
   NASA has released details of tests conducted on Galileo's radio
isotope thermoelectric generators. But the protest group is
skeptical of space agency claims that there is virtually no chance
of an explosion that would destroy the nuclear canisters and release
life-threatening radioactive fallout.
</TEXT>
