<DOCNO> AP890917-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-89 1918EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-YeltsinVisit     09-17 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yeltsin Visit,0453</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yeltsin Found Americans Friendly</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SANDRA WALEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet politician Boris Yeltsin wrapped up an
eight-day tour of the United States on Sunday, and said he had found
Americans to be ``industrious, friendly, full of good humor and
vitality.''
   Yeltsin's first visit to the United States included meetings with
President Bush and Vice President Dan Quayle, meetings with NASA
officials, speaking engagements at colleges and a trip to an
American grocery store.
   Yeltsin, an outspoken critic of Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev,
spoke Sunday to about 500 people at a $100-a-plate luncheon
sponsored by the University of Miami Graduate School of
International Studies.
   He said the political situation in the Soviet Union was
``extremely difficult'' and the Communist Party was ``on the verge
of crisis.''
   ``We have not seen an evolution of power from the party to the
congress,'' said Yeltsin, a member of parliament and former member
of the ruling Politburo.
   ``The party has got to be subordinate to the Congress of People's
Deputies. ... That's because the Politburo is leaning too far to the
right and pulling Gorbachev with it,'' he said through an
interpreter.
   While Yeltsin assailed the conservative elements in the Soviet
Union that were stalling reform, he assured, ``We are profoundly
convinced that glasnost and democratization of our society are
inevitable processes.''
   The luncheon was the last event scheduled for Yeltsin, who was to
leave Miami later Sunday en route to the Soviet Union.
   In Houston on Saturday, Yeltsin followed a meeting with NASA
officials about possible U.S.-Soviet space links with an eye-opening
visit to a grocery store, saying such plenty could cause a
revolution in his country.
   ``Even the Politburo doesn't have this choice,'' Yeltsin said, as
he looked over fish and meat at Randall's Supermarket in Clear Lake,
near the Johnson Space Center. ``Not even Mr. Gorbachev.''
   When he roamed the grocery store aisles, nodding his head in
amazement at the array of food and other products, Yeltsin commented
that if the Soviet people who stand in lines for groceries ever saw
a U.S. supermarket, ``there would be a revolution.''
   Yeltsin tasted free samples of cheese and produce and ogled rows
of meat. ``We don't have this much meat in the Soviet Union,'' he
said.
   He stopped several shoppers and workers, asking about the food
they selected and the cost.
   One store employee offered him a single yellow rose to remember
his trip to the Lone Star State and another gave him a bag of snacks.
   ``Is this what you give a starving Russian?'' Yeltsin joked.
``You should add some soap; we need that, too.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890917-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-89 1921EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua     09-17 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nicaraguan Defense Minister Says Rebels Are Disbanding</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S.-backed rebel force fighting
Nicaragua's Sandinista government is disbanding but won't vanish all
at once, despite a Central American peace accord, the Nicaraguan
defense minister said Sunday.
   ``It won't be sudden, like an earthquake. They'll just dry up,''
Humberto Ortega told reporters in Mexico City.
   He said only 500 rebels, known as Contras, turned themselves in
under a repatriation program called for in last month's peace accord
signed in Tela, Honduras, by five Central American presidents.
   But he said the Contra force was crumbling through quiet
desertion.
   ``A lot of them don't trust us enough to turn themselves in.
They're just putting their guns away and waiting to see what
happens,'' said Ortega, who represented Nicaragua in Mexico's
Independence Day celebrations.
   The Central American presidents signed the agreement Aug. 7 that
called for dismantling the Contras, most of whom are based in
Honduras along the border with Nicaragua. In return, Nicaraguan
President Daniel Ortega promised democratic elections, now scheduled
for Feb. 25.
   Humberto Ortega said the opposition coalition's presidential
candidate, Violeta Barrios de Chamorro, was allied with U.S.
interests.
   Mrs. Chamorro is the widow of Pedro Joaquin Chamorro, whose
assassination helped spark the Sandinista revolution that overthrew
President Anastasio Somoza in July 1979. She served on the first
post-revolutionary junta but resigned after a year and joined the
opposition that formed mainly because of the Sandinistas surge to
the left and its links with Cuba and the Soviet Union.
   Humberto Ortega said the Sandinista party will choose its
candidate on Sept. 24. He said he thought his brother, President
Daniel Ortega, would be the best nominee.
   Daniel Ortega's nomination is considered a virtual certainty.
   When asked what the army would do if Mrs. Chamorro and the
opposition wins, Humberto Ortega said the defense forces would not
try to control the government. But, he said, the Sandinista army
``will never be an army that serves a dominant class.''
   The Aug. 7 agreement calls for dismantling the Contras by Dec. 8,
but Humberto Ortega said their complete demobilization was unlikely.
He added if the Honduran base camps are shut the rebellion will
eventually die out.
   ``We've already reached a state of relative peace,'' he said.
``Once we hold elections we'll be able to reach a state of complete
peace.''
   The defense minister said about 60 people, including civilians,
soldiers and rebels, were killed in fighting in Nicaragua last month.
   He said there have been about 50 clashes a month between troops
and rebels, down from about 500 monthly before the United States cut
off military aid to the Contras in 1988. Non-lethal U.S. aid is
scheduled to continue through February.
   Humberto Ortega estimated the number of Contras in Nicaragua at
2,000 and the number in Honduran camps at 4,500, about one-quarter
the number Contra leaders claim.
   Journalists estimate there were more than 6,000 fighters in the
main Contra camp in Honduras last month, down sharply from more than
10,000 in February.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
