<FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-89 1930EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     09-17 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>Says North Korean Spy Escort Defects</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A North Korean civilian, described by
Seoul authorities as a spy escort, defected to South Korea early
Sunday across the 2.5 mile-wide Demilitarized Zone, the Defense
Ministry announced.
   It said Suh Yong chul, a member of North Korea's ruling Workers'
(Communist) Party, surrendered at a South Korean marine outpost on
Kanghwa island at 3:45 a.m. after swimming across a river on the
western border.
   Ministry spokesman Kim Ji-wook identified Suh as an escort of
North Korean agents sent to South Korea for espionage. He gave no
further details.
   South Korea accuses North Korea of frequently sending spies
across the DMZ, established under the truce that ended the Korean
War in 1953.
   Suh was the seventh North Korean to defect to South Korea in less
than two months.
   In the latest incident on Sept.10 three North Koreans _ an army
second lieutenant, a staff sergeant and a civilian nurse _ crossed
through a minefield inside the DMZ and swam across a river on the
westen front.
   North Korea, in a report monitored in Tokyo Sunday, said the
United States sent a new ambassador, Donald Gregg, to South Korea to
help stop the anti-American movement.
   The official Workers Party newspaper Rodong Shinmun described
Gregg as ``an old `secret agent' who has accumulated experience in
the U.S. Central Intelligence Agency for nearly 30 years.''
   It said the ``U.S. imperialists have dispatched Gregg to South
Korea with a view to quelling the South Korean people's
anti-American sentiment for independence and reunification`` with
North Korea.
   Gregg arrived Saturday to take up his post in Seoul, where he
served as the U.S. CIA station chief in 1973-76.
   There have been increasing demands by some South Korean political
groups for withdrawal of the 43,000 U.S. troops stationed in South
Korea under a mutual defense treaty.
   Gregg said on arrival, ``As long as the Korean government and the
Korean public share with us the judgment that there is a need for
our presence, we will be here to assist in maintaining peace on the
peninsula.''
   The peninsula was divided at the end of World War II in 1945 into
the communist North and capitalist South. The United States was one
of 16 nations that sent troops to South Korea's aid after North
Korea invaded in 1950. American troops remained to help in defense
after the war ended in an armistice in 1953.
</TEXT>
