<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Tankers 1stLd-Writethru a0691 09-17 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Tankers, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0691,0427</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tanker Collision Spills Oil in North Sea</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmitting a0740 to fix header. LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE
with slick spreading, aircraft treating it with dispersants; Pickup 3rd,
`The Fiona...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HULL, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two oil tankers collided off the northeast
coast of England early Sunday, caught fire and spilled more than
300,000 gallons of crude oil into the North Sea, the coast guard
said.
   No injuries were reported aboard the Liberian-registered Phillips
Oklahoma or the Maltese-registered Fiona, and authorities expressed
confidence the 20-mile-long by seven-mile-wide oil slick could be
dispersed.
   Six aircraft sprayed the spreading slick with dispersants
throughout the day. A coast guard spokesman said much of the oil had
broken into patches and there were no reports of oil coming ashore.
   The Fiona, which anchored when the early morning collision
occurred, was damaged in the bow while the Oklahoma, which was
moving, was damaged in the stern, said coast guard spokesman David
Clempson.
   He would not comment on who was responsible for the collision. He
said an investigation would be conducted by the Department of
Transport.
   Clempson said helicopters flew 20 firemen to the vessels, and
five fire-fighting tugs were at the scene. Five British minesweepers
on a NATO exercise were put on standby.
   Firefighters said it took more than three hours to contain the
flames aboard the Phillips Oklahoma, but the fire aboard the Fiona
was quickly controlled.
   By mid-morning, Clempson said, the Phillips Oklahoma fires had
been extinguished and the source of the oil leakage had been
stopped. Both ships were at anchor off Spurn Head in the Mouth of
the Humber, about 150 miles north of London, he said.
   The Phillips 66 Co., operators of the Phillips Oklahoma, said the
oil spilled from a slop tank through a hole two yards above the
waterline.
   ``Most of that will have probably been burnt up in the fire,''
Clempson said. ``The way it is heading it doesn't appear to be
coming ashore.''
   The Phillips Oklahoma carried 56,000 tons of crude oil, and the
Fiona had 46,500 tons of refined oil aboard, Clempson said.
   In London, a spokesman for the Department of Transport said
aerial surveys indicated the spill was minor.
   Seventeen of 26 crew members were evacuated from the Phillips
Oklahoma. One crew member from the Fiona was recovered from the sea
by the minesweeper HMS Middleton after he jumped overboard. He was
being treated for shock, and the rest of the ship's 30-member crew
remained aboard.
</TEXT>
