<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 2ndLd-Writethru   09-17 0753</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0700,0778</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moslems Voice Support for Peace Plan, Aoun Critical, Soldiers Battle</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with Aoun comment; no pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem leaders and Lebanon's Christian
patriarch voiced support for a new Arab peace proposal Sunday, but
Christian army commander Michel Aoun rejected key parts of the plan
and fighting continued.
   Police said one person was killed and 14 were wounded in
nightlong artillery clashes in and around Beirut. That raised the
toll to at least 915 killed and 2,699 wounded since the latest
fighting broke out on March 8.
   Gen. Aoun rejected key clauses of the seven-point peace plan
announced Saturday by a three-member Arab League committee.
   In a televised interview, Aoun said he would not appoint a
representative to a Lebanese security committee that would oversee a
cease-fire under the peace plan.
   ``I won't accept at all a Lebanese-Lebanese committee. This is
what the Syrians wanted to deceive the world and say the clashes
have been among Lebanese factions,'' Aoun said.
   Syria has refused to take part in a security committee,
maintaining the conflict is between Aoun and his Lebanese foes. But
Syrian troops, in Lebanon under a 1976 Arab League peacekeeping
mandate, allied with Moslem militias as a main party in the latest
violence.
   Aoun also criticized the committee's call for Parliament to meet
outside Lebanon to discuss political reforms demanded by the Moslems.
   ``First Lebanon should be free of all occupations, then reforms
could be worked out,'' he said. That was a reference to Syria and
Israel, which controls a border strip in south Lebanon.
   Aoun said he would abide by the cease-fire if Syria did. ``If
they don't put away their guns, we'll continue to respond to their
fire.''
   He renewed his attack on Washington, saying the U.S. government
was covering up for Syria. Washington withdrew its embassy staff
from Beirut on Sept. 6 after Christian demonstrators surrounded the
embassy compound demanding U.S. action to help drive the Syrians out.
   Saudi Arabia's foreign minister, Prince Saud Faisal, arrived
unexpectedly Sunday in the Syrian capital, Damascus, for talks with
Syrian leaders on putting the peace plan into effect.
   He delivered a letter to President Hafez Assad from King Fahd of
Saudi Arabia, according to officials who would not disclose its
contents. He then met with Vice President Abdul-Halim Khaddam,
architect of Syria's military intervention in Lebanon.
   Saud was to fly to Baghdad later Sunday for discussions in Iraq,
Syria's archrival and Aoun's weapons supplier.
   The Arab League committee comprising Fahd, King Hassan II of
Morocco and President Chadli Bendjedid of Algeria apppealed urgently
Saturday for an immediate cease-fire. Its several previous calls for
a truce have been ignored.
   Lebanon's acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, a Sunni Moslem vying
for power with Aoun, welcomed Saturday's call. He called it ``a
chance to end the crisis that might not be repeated.''
   The plan does not call for Syria to withdraw its 40,000 troops,
whom Aoun charges have betrayed their mandate by siding with the
Moslems.
   The Arab League statement also said Algerian diplomat Lakhdar
al-Ibrahimi will head a security committee to supervise the
cease-fire and monitor ships to ensure no weapons reach the warring
factions.
   That will affect Aoun more than the Syrians. His only supply
route is by sea, as the enclave's three landward sides are ringed by
Syrian forces and their allies. Syria's supply lines run through
territory it controls.
   Fahd, Hassan and Bendjedid called on ``all parties'' to stop
arming the warring factions and said they have received ``positive
responses in this regard.''
   Patriarch Nasrallah Sfeir, spiritual leader of the Christian
Maronite sect, thanked the Arab League committee for ``the great
effort it is exerting to silence the guns.''
   Shiite Moslem militia chieftain Nabih Berri, one of Syria's main
allies in Lebanon, said he ``welcomes the security arrangements
included in the committee's plan, which are capable of halting the
cycle of violence.''
   Current fighting in the 14-year-old civil war erupted when Aoun
blockaded illegal ports run by Moslem militias and Syria responded
by besieging the 310-square-mile Christian heartland north of Beirut.
   The Arab League committee has invited Lebanon's 99 legislators to
meet Sept. 30 to ``discuss and prepare'' political reforms to end
the war that has killed more than 150,000 people.
   Maronites have dominated Lebanese politics since independence
from France in 1943, when Christians were considered the majority.
Now Moslems constitute about 55 percent of the country's 4 million
people and demand political equality.
</TEXT>
