<SECOND>AM-Chamorro-Miami,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nicaraguan Opposition Candidate Visits Miami</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Nicaragua</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MH5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 2,000 Nicaraguan exiles greeted Nicaraguan
presidential candidate Violeta Barrios de Chamorro on Sunday in her
first U.S. visit since being nominated as leader of the
anti-Sandinista factions.
   Mrs. Chamorro, wife of slain newspaper publisher Pedro Joaquin
Chamorro, was mobbed by supporters when she arrived in Miami, a city
that received an influx of more than 100,000 impoverished Nicaraguan
refugees last year.
   She criticized the Sandinista government for human rights
violations and for causing the country's economic problems, and she
appealed to Nicaraguans abroad to consider returning to their
homeland if her opposition party is successful in the Feb. 25
elections.
   ``The hour has sounded for liberty in Nicaragua,'' she told the
crowd in Spanish. ``But the liberty is for Nicaraguans and the
reconciliation of all the people.''
   Mrs. Chamorro's visit came two days after the Bush administration
bowed to congressional pressure and abandoned a plan to funnel about
$2 million in government funds to her campaign through the
U.S.-financed National Endowment for Democracy.
   But administration officials say they will encourage private and
foreign groups to donate money to Mrs. Chamorro.
   The National Opposition Union, an anti-government coalition known
by its Spanish initials UNO, selected Mrs. Chamorro as its
presidential candidate earlier this month. The Sandinistas are
expected to endorse President Daniel Ortega for re-election.
   Mrs. Chamorro, 59, a Roman Catholic, pledged religious freedom
and said her administration would emphasize a free-market economy in
Nicaragua, one of the poorest nation's in the Western Hemisphere.
She also called on the United States to grant work permits to
Nicaraguan refugees.
   ``The communists are contrary to the history of Nicaragua and the
culture of the Nicaraguan people,'' said Mrs. Chamorro, who took
over the daily La Prensa newspaper after her husband was gunned down
in 1978.
   Mrs. Chamorro's detractors cite her political inexperience and
her brief term in the revolutionary government. A small band of
opponents who back other rebel leaders marched outside the
amphitheater Sunday.
   A $100-a-plate fund-raising dinner for Mrs. Chamorro was also
planned for Monday in Miami.
   Former Argentine President Raul Alfonsin and former President
Jimmy Carter are expected to head a commission to supervise and
observe the February elections.
