<HEAD>Three Killed in Alabama Plane Crash; Two in California</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A small plane low on fuel crashed Sunday while trying to land on
a highway in Alabama, killing three men, and two people were killed
in California when their plane crashed between lanes of a freeway.
   A 6-year-old boy was the only survivor of the eastern Alabama
crash, said Houston County Deputy Sheriff Eddie Ingram.
   The boy was pulled from the plane after rescuers, carrying
buckets of water from a nearby river, doused flames that had
engulfed the aircraft. Truck drivers also stopped and used fire
extinguishers.
   Ingram said the rescuers lifted the aircraft by the tail section
and one man crawled beneath and pulled the boy out.
   ``If it hadn't been for them there's no doubt the child would
have perished,'' Ingram said. ``It was a heroic effort.''
   The pilot, Roger Kenneth Parmer, 47, informed flight controllers
about 3:30 p.m. that he was low on fuel and trying to reach a
landing strip at Cedar Springs, Ga.
   The plane struck a power line and crashed in a wooded area in
Gordon, Ala., near the Georgia state line, Ingram said.
   Also killed were Edward Prather, 55, and Kenneth S. Partridge,
54, all from LaGrange, Ga., said Houston County Coroner Robert Byrd.
   The boy, Brandon Parmer, was in guarded condition at Southeast
Alabama Medical Center, said hospital spokesman Ray Griffith.
   In California, a man and woman were killed when their twin-engine
Cessna crashed between the northbound and southbound lanes of
Interstate 15 at Cajon Junction, about 55 miles northeast of Los
Angeles.
   Authorities were trying to determine the victims' identities.
   Officials from the Federal Aviation Administration and the
National Transportation Safety Board were investigating where the
flight originated and where it was headed.
   Authorities learned of the accident through a telephone call from
a motorist, said San Bernardino County Sheriff's Sgt. David Lau.
When deputies arrived, they found the plane in flames and debris
scattered 100 yards away.
</TEXT>
