<FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-89 2134EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ButteHousing 1stld-writethru a0726 09-17 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Butte Housing, 1st ld-writethru, a0726,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>HUD Audit Questions Accounting Records</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs lead to recast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Butte, Mont., Public Housing Authority
failed to follow procedures in granting money for housing projects,
according to a recent audit by the Department of Housing and Urban
Development.
   Because of the shortcomings, HUD ``cannot be sure'' money awarded
for the projects was being spent ``in the most efficient and
economical way,'' said the audit report released Aug. 21.
   The Butte housing authority operates 356 low-income housing units
_ 214 for senior citizens and 142 for families. The assistance
program provides money to improve their physical condition and
upgrade their management. As of March 1989, $4.8 million had been
approved for the projects.
   The audit was conducted in April and May of this year.
   The housing authority made budget changes without following
written procedures, particularly concerning the addition to the
1986-87 budgets of $639,000 to remove lead-based paint and $100,000
to repair or demolish a building, the audit said. Because of those
changes, other items budgeted for those years, such as $251,000 for
water heaters and heating units, were postponed to 1988.
   HUD regulations call for submission of a formal budget revision
when a major change is made.
   The audit found that the Butte housing authority charged expenses
to the wrong accounts, didn't keep adequate accounting records,
didn't use available resources such as $17,000 worth of computer
equipment, requested money before spending what it already had and
failed to cancel invoices to ensure bills weren't paid more than
once.
   The audit also determined that the authority didn't follow HUD
requirements in awarding contracts. Among other discrepancies, the
authority failed to advertise or obtain HUD approval for contracts
over $10,000, as required.
   Butte did meet HUD requirements for developing and implementing a
five-year plan to meet the projects' physical needs but didn't
provide a rolling five-year plan, which would outline future
financial needs.
   The Inspector General's office instructed the Butte Public
Housing Authority to provide within 60 days a report on action taken
to remedy the problems or why action is not needed.
</TEXT>
