<FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-89 2134EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r e BC-Theater     09-17 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Carnage, A Comedy' by Adam Simon and Tim Robbins Opens Off-Broadway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The title is ``Carnage, A Comedy,'' as if authors
Adam Simon and Tim Robbins had to reassure theatergoers it was all
right to laugh.
   Not many did at a preview of this messy, meandering and mirthless
satire of religious evangelism that opened Sunday at the New York
Shakespeare Festival Public Theater.
   The play comes from The Actors' Gang, an acting ensemble from Los
Angeles that has been putting on productions since 1981 on the West
Coast and performed ``Carnage'' at the Edinburgh Festival in
Scotland before coming here. It wasn't worth the trip.
   Robbins, an actor best known for the movie ``Bull Durham,'' and
Simon have concocted an unfunny and heavy-handed comic strip
masquerading as a play. One of their main characters is a preacher
named Cotton Slocum, a rotund, shaggy-haired charlatan who sells
religion as if it were snake oil at a place called God's Happy Acre.
``This is not a non-profit organization,'' Slocum insists. ``This is
a church.''
   The minister and his carefully coiffured wife Tipper are always
in the market for new ways to make money. He devises a Prayer Walk
during which he will pound the pavement for the Lord as well as for
monetary pledges to finance his new religious theme park.
   Slocum's assistant is a right-wing zombie named Deacon Tack who
trains paramilitary cadets on the side. The man combines the fervor
of Ollie North and the personality of Bela Lugosi.
   Mixed into this fanatic folderol is a sweet, dim-witted housewife
named Dot who truly believes in Slocum and her husband Ralph, who
participates in Tack's military maneuvers. They all come together in
the desert during an incomprehensible second act. It deteriorates
into lunatic ravings, mostly by Tack about the upcoming Armageddon
in which the permissive society, as well as the Commies, will be
vanquished.
   The acting is more enthusiastic than competent, but Lee Arenberg
is fine as the money-hungry minister, Shannon Holt projects the
simple sincerity of the deluded housewife, and Ned Bellamy is
positively creepy as the looney deacon.
   But a smirkiness and condescension pervade the proceedings.
What's more, the play can't compete with the real thing. Jim and
Tammy Bakker, Jimmy Swaggart, Ollie North and all the rest of the
people ``Carnage'' attempts to harpoon are much more theatrical _
and funnier _ in real life than anything Simon and Robbins have put
on stage.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890917-0071 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-89 2140EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-IowaInvestigation 1stLd-Writethru a0732 09-17 0850</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iowa Investigation, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0732,0866</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy Stands By Report on Cause of Iowa Explosion</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts two grafs after 6th graf, `Hartwig's family...', to
UPDATE with Ohio congresswoman comment. Picks up 7th graf, `The 7,007....'.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy is standing by its conclusion that
a USS Iowa crewman probably deliberately caused a blast aboard the
battleship that killed 47 men, despite a report that the battleship
was being used for high-explosive experiments.
   Transcripts from the Navy investigation of the April 19 blast
showed that an improper type of gun powder was being used
experimentally when the explosion occurred inside the ship's No.2
turret, which has three 16-inch guns, Media General News Service
reported Sunday.
   ``Everything was very carefully considered,'' said Cmdr. Mark
Baker, a Navy spokesman at the Pentagon, who defended the Navy's
official report on the explosion.
   The Pentagon report said circumstantial evidence indicated
gunner's mate Clayton Hartwig of Cleveland intentionally sparked the
explosion. However, the report said it would be impossible to prove
because all those nearby died in the explosion, including Hartwig.
   But the detailed transcripts showed that the Navy command that
requested the experiments _ the Naval Sea Systems Command _ was the
same agency that performed the tests that led to the Navy's
conclusion about the cause of the explosion, released earlier this
month.
   Hartwig's family has requested a congressional investigation.
   U.S. Rep. Mary Rose Oakar, D-Ohio, who has consulted with the
Hartwig family, said Sunday she will hold a meeting in her
Washington office with Navy investigators on Monday to question them
about the Iowa report.
   ``We're concerned about the safety of the individuals aboard any
of these battleships,'' she said. ``We've known for some time now
there were some questions about that gunpowder ... It certainly
appears they didn't continue their own investigation. Everything
leads to asking them why they didn't conclude that some of it was
their fault.''
   The 7,007 pages of transcripts of Navy investigators and
interviewees was made available to the public, but only at the
Pentagon and only for one day, the day the official report was
issued.
   The transcripts showed Iowa gunners were firing an experimental
load from the No. 2 turret with high-strength powder not approved
for the weight of the projectile. According to the transcripts, the
tests were designed to improve the accuracy and range of the ship's
antiquated 16-inch guns.
   The experiments involved the use of a bagged powder, called Delta
846, with 2,700-pound projectiles. That was in violation of warnings
written in large letters on each container of D-846 powder bags that
said not to use it with the heavier projectiles because it would
create too much pressure and heat inside the gun barrel.
   Apparently to avoid that, the ship's gunners were using five
110-pound bags of the powder instead of the normal six-bag charge.
   The battleship's commander, Capt. Fred B. Moosally, told
investigators that he did not know a five-bag charge was going to be
used in the No. 2 turret.
   Master Chief S.P. Skelly, who had won a reputation throughout the
service as a ballistics expert, was in charge of the experiments.
   Moosally said Skelly did not brief him on any of the experiments.
   ``A lot of these things that I'm hearing about, it seems to me
they rightfully belong somewhere other than at sea, at least until
they're approved through all the shore testing and directed to be
conducted at sea,'' Moosally said.
   The investigators pursued the possibility that Hartwig, who took
over as gun captain in a last-minute roster change, perhaps was
confused by seeing only five bags of powder delivered at the breech
instead of six, and that in the confusion the powder bags were
rammed into the barrel too quickly, splitting a bag open and
igniting the powder by the heat of friction.
   The friction theory was eliminated by a series of tests under the
direction of the Naval Sea Systems Command at the Naval Surface
Warfare Center at Dahlgren, Va., the same command that encouraged
the experiments with the D-846 powder aboard the Iowa.
   But those findings contradicted all previous Navy literature
warning of ignition of powder bags by friction.
   Tests at Dahlgren and other Navy sites found that trace elements
present in the breech of the center gun of the No. 2 turret could
not be found after firings with normal powder. Those elements were
found, however, when a timing device and battery were inserted
between the powder bags and the gun was fired.
   The Navy has suggested that Hartwig could have inserted a timer
into the powder charge.
   However, the investigation transcripts showed that the breech of
the center gun was open at the time of the explosion, and those
trace elements could have been blown into the breech by the fireball
that swept through the turret.
   Media General, a communications company based in Richmond,
publishes the Richmond Times-Dispatch, the Richmond News Leader, the
Tampa (Fla.) Tribune and the Winston-Salem (N.C.) Journal, and
operates TV station WXFL in Tampa, WCBD in Charleston, S.C., and
WJKS in Jacksonville, Fla.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
