<FIRST>r i AM-Norway-Conference     09-17 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Norway-Conference,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Military Analysts Say Soviet Changes Unpredictable</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Changes in the Soviet bloc are developing so
fast it is impossible to tell were they will lead, military
specialists from the East and West blocs said at the end Sunday of a
three-day conference.
   Military analysts from Warsaw Pact nations were invited for the
first time in 20 years to address the annual conference of the
International Institute for Strategic Studies _ IISS.
   ``The general feeling was that the Soviets want reform at least
as much as they want order,'' Francois Heisbourg, director of the
London-based private institute, said in an interview.
   But continued disorder might spark the violent breakup of the
Soviet Union, Heisbourg said, citing opinions expressed among those
present.
   The 381 private and government military analysts discussed, among
other issues, the consequences of Soviet reform and negotiations
between the superpowers. Heisbourg said it was institute policy not
to disclose details of the closed-door debate.
   ``There is currently an atmosphere of detente,'' said Heisbourg,
a former defense advisor to the French government. Talks between the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization and the Warsaw Pact on
conventional arms parity in Europe were promising, he said.
   Opinions ranged from ``very pessimistic to moderately
optimistic'' among the specialists from 17 nations on Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's chances for completing his economic
and political reforms, he said.
   The situation shifts so quickly that some authors said their own
papers, written two months ago, were already out of date.
   ``It is in everyone's interest for reforms to succeed,''
Heisbourg said. ``The bottom line is that it will be difficult and
take a long time.''
   East bloc delegates ``acknowledged grave problems in the Soviet
Union'' such as the ethnic strife in provinces wanting a stronger
national identity, Heisbourg said.
   ``Nationalism and populism are symptoms of ailments ... but
Gorbachev is in charge. There is no coherent opposition to challenge
him.''
   The independent institute, which was founded in 1958 and has
about 3,000 members from 76 countries, studies strategic issues.
</TEXT>
