<FIRST>r a AM-SouthernGovernors     09-17 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Southern Governors,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Infant Mortality Tops Southern Governors' Opening</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THERESA HUMPHREY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Businesses could help improve the South's
infant mortality and low birth rate statistics by educating pregnant
employees in prenatal care, Southern governors were told Sunday.
   ``The South continues to lag behind the nation'' with an infant
mortality rate of 12.0 per 1,000 live births, compared with a
national rate of 10.0, according to Arkansas Gov. Bill Clinton,
chairman of the Southern Corporate Coalition to Improve Maternal and
Child Health.
   Joe Taylor, plant manager for Sunbeam Appliance Co. in Coushatta,
La., described his company's mandatory prenatal education program
that began in 1986 after statistics for the previous two years
showed 11 employees had premature babies that cost the company $2
million in medical care.
   The prenatal education program costs the company $10,000 per
year, and in 1987, Taylor said there were no premature babies born
to employees. In 1988, he said there was one premature baby that was
hospitalized for only nine weeks.
   ``We've saved a great deal of money,'' he said, noting that
before the classes, the company was spending about $25,000 in health
care costs per premature baby. Now the costs per birth are about
$3,500.
   Conferees at the Southern Governors' Association annual meeting
shared ideas on how businesses could help keep babies alive past
their first year.
   The association represents 17 states and two territories.
   Clinton said Southern states are reducing infant mortality rates,
but low birth weight rates remain high, although figures were not
available. Low birth weight babies are those born weighing 5 pounds
or less.
   ``I'll bet you the low birth rate is high because employees don't
have the education. I think it's because we haven't reached this
employee population like we should,'' he said.
   Clinton said he hopes to call a conference in Arkansas late this
year or in early 1990 to address the problems with business leaders
and health care providers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
