<FIRST>r i AM-Haiti-Anniversary     09-17 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Haiti-Anniversary,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Avril Speaks On First Anniversary Of Coup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ National leader Lt. Gen. Prosper
Avril on Sunday promised democratic reforms and economic progress in
a speech marking the first anniversary of the coup that put him in
power.
   In the address broadcast on the state-run media from the National
Palace, Avril said, ``Our quest is to promote the human, economic,
social, and political rights of Haitians.''
   He asked the international community to back efforts to return
this impoverished Caribbean nation to civilian rule.
   On Sept. 17, 1988, rank-and-file soldiers outraged by what they
called state-sponsored violence ousted former military ruler Lt.
Gen. Henri Namphy in a bloodless coup. They chose Avril to head a
new government.
   The soldiers, mostly of the Presidential Guard, also demanded a
return to democratic rule and a respect for human rights.
   Some Haitians are skeptical that Avril will do what he has
promised.
   ``Hope has been reborn in an eventual solution to our problems,
even if the relief which Haitians felt at the overthrow of Namphy
has not developed into confidence in Avril,'' said Leopold
Berlanger, director of the Haitian Research and Development
Institute.
   In March, Avril partially restored the 1987 Constitution that
Namphy had suspended in July 1988. Avril has pledged to turn over
power to an elected government and allowed the creation of an
independent Electoral Council.
   That council is expected to announce later this month a date for
elections.
   The U.S. government granted $10 million in surplus wheat to Haiti
in June.
   Washington resumed direct government aid suspended after aborted
elections of 1987, when thugs protected by soldiers killed at least
34 voters at polling stations.
   Hundreds of allegedly corrupt soldiers and officers have been
discharged from the army since Avril took power.
   On Dec. 14 his government signed five international human-rights
conventions. However, human rights groups charge that abuses, often
perpetrated by soldiers, are still common.
   Haiti has been govered by military-dominated governments since
dictator Jean-Claude Duvalier fled the country during violent
demonstrations that ended about three decades of Duvalier family
rule. He now lives in exile in France.
</TEXT>
