<FIRST>r a AM-BadCheckSchool     09-17 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bad Check School,0226</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bounced Checks Send Writers Back to School</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Graduates of the Bad Check Writer's School
probably won't be hanging their diplomas on the wall, but
authorities hope next time they put pen to paper the results will at
least be legal.
   The school, held at various locations on weekends, is the last
step in a pilot program designed to keep misdemeanor offenders from
clogging the courts.
   Those who have written bad checks under $200 must reimburse their
creditors, pay a $65 fine and spend four hours in class learning
ethics and how to balance their checkbooks.
   ``It's dumb mistakes that brings most of us here today,'' student
Larry Logsdon, 35, said at a recent session. ``I know I've been
kicking myself ever since.''
   Logsdon, a vitamin salesman from Glendora, wrote a bad check to a
supermarket for $75.
   ``I thought I had enough money,'' he said.
   Since 1986, the program has returned $1.2 million to merchants.
It is expected to double in size next month, said Capt. Edmund M.
Aleks, who heads the program for the district attorney's special
operation division.
   To date, more than 5,000 people have been graduated from the Bad
Check Writer's School. To earn their diplomas, the students must
know how to balance a bank statement and a checkbook.
</TEXT>
