<HEAD>Exxon Tanker That Lost Power Repaired</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An empty Exxon oil tanker that lost power in the
Strait of Juan de Fuca was repaired Sunday and sailed for Alaska,
the Coast Guard said.
   The tanker lost power Friday night about 33 miles west of Port
Angeles.
   The ship drifted for about an hour in the strait before regaining
some maneuverability and was escorted by the Coast Guard to Port
Angeles.
   Coast Guard Lt. Cmdr. Richard Fitzpatrick said a malfunction in
the electronic components of the 810-foot Exxon San Francisco was
repaired in Port Angeles and the ship headed for Valdez, Alaska.
   The Strait of Juan de Fuca separates the Olympic Peninsula in
Washington State from Canada's Vancouver Island and links Puget
Sound with the Pacific Ocean. Tankers, many carrying Alaska crude
oil, travel the strait regularly to reach refineries along Puget
Sound.
