<SECOND>AM-Mine Explosion,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Last Two of 10 Coal Miners Killed in Mine Blast Buried</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL DE LA GARZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The last two of 10 coal miners killed in a
western Kentucky mine explosion were buried Sunday, and residents
said the tragedy soon will be forgotten because such disasters are
common in coal country.
   Funeral services were held for Anthony T. McElroy, 36, of
Providence, and Curtis W. Scott, 47, of Madisonville.
   Seven victims of Wednesday's blast at Pyro Mining Co.'s William
Station Mine in Wheatcroft, which company officials speculate was
fueled by methane gas, were buried Saturday. The other victim was
buried Friday.
   The accident ``will call everybody's attention for a while, but
six months from now they'll forget about it,'' said former coal
miner John Clark of Wheatcroft.
   Clark and a truck driver who hauls coal said mining accidents are
nothing new because running coal is dangerous, especially
underground.
   Meanwhile, the investigation into the accident _ the nation's
worst mine disaster since 1984 _ was delayed for a third consecutive
day Sunday because of dangerous levels of methane gas at the
underground facility, said federal Mine Safety and Health
Administration spokesman Frank O'Gorman.
   MSHA has approved a plan, with modications, which Pyro submitted
to rectify the problem, O'Gorman said. ``The investigation has not
officially started,'' he said.
   O'Gorman said he did not know when the methane problem would be
cleared.
</TEXT>
