<FIRST>u a AM-Emmys-Roev.Wade     09-17 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Emmys-Roe v. Wade,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Emmy-Winning Star Says Controversial `Roe vs. Wade' Had Pro-Choice
Message</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Roe vs. Wade,'' probably the most
controversial show of the past television season, lived up to its
outspoken reputation in winning two top Emmys at the 41st Annual
Primetime Emmy Awards show.
   Holly Hunter, who won the Emmy for best actress in a miniseries
or special for her starring role in the NBC movie, said in her
acceptance speech that the movie made a case for a woman's right to
abortion.
   Hunter, in thanking Norma McCorvey, whose fight for a legal
abortion led to the historic 1973 Supreme Court decision, said she
``continued to fight to keep women from being second-class citizens
and for refusing to give up her right to reproductive choice.''
   ``Roe vs. Wade,'' which also shared the outstanding drama-comedy
special Emmy with ``Day One,'' was subject to more than 20 rewrites
because NBC was concerned that the movie would come out in favor of
a woman's right to abortion.
   The movie was abandoned by advertisers and targeted by
fundamentalist Christian groups, who claimed the movie was biased.
   Speaking backstage after collecting her statute, Hunter, an
activist in the abortion rights movement, said the movie did indeed
have a point of view.
   ``It can't be right down the middle,'' she said. ``The story was
a woman fighting for a pro-choice right.''
   Michael Manheim, the executive producer of ``Roe vs. Wade,'' said
the movie took four years to bring to the screen.
   Said Hunter: ``I'd like to thank NBC for getting this movie on
the air.''
</TEXT>
