<FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-89 1520EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-KiddieBusiness     09-17 0622</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kiddie Business,0644</SECOND>
<HEAD>Children's Products Market Takes Off With Baby Boom</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The convention hall may be full of playpens and
cribs, pacifiers and cradles, but there is little child's play at
the 20th annual Juvenile Products Manufacturers Association trade
show _ where companies come for show-and-tell in the $1.95 billion
market in wares for the under-3 gang.
   There are even products that help combat yuppie guilt for being
at work instead of at home with the kids.
   Now that baby boomers are having babies themselves the market has
taken off, spurred by the higher salaries of professional,
two-career families who wait until later in life to have children.
   Also, fewer children per family means more money per child,
association members said.
   Tastes also have changed, with price often being of little
object, said Shirley Pepys, the trade group's vice president and
head of her own firm, which makes coordinated nursery bedding and
other infant products.
   For example, her Noel-Joanna Inc., which markets products under
the NoJo brand, last year introduced a Battenberg lace crib
ensemble, complete with elegant canopy. The price: about $600.
   ``We just did it for fun,'' Mrs. Pepys said. ``It's turned into
one of our best sellers.''
   Such extravagance doesn't last long. ``While they'll spend $600
on the crib bedding, which they'll use for two years, they balk at
spending $100 for a comforter for a bunk bed. At (age) 2,
practicality takes over.''
   Before then, however, parents will shell out the bucks.
   Frances Blakey, the association's director of public relations,
said studies indicate parents spend $30,000 on a child up until age
5, about 30 percent of all they'll spend before the child reaches 18.
   And there are so many ways to spend it.
   Playskool Baby Inc., a wholly owned subsidiary of toymaker Hasbro
Inc., has a three-sided toothbrush among its abundance of infant
care products _ many adorned with Mickey Mouse and Kermit the Frog _
to pitch during the show this weekend at the Dallas Apparel Mart.
   Playskool is one of the large players in the industry,
manufacturing about six pieces of product for every birth in the
country last year, said President Bob Stebenne.
   But Mrs. Pepys said only about 20 of the 250 or so companies at
the show have annual sales of $20 million or more. Most of the firms
would be considered small businesses, she said.
   Many of the companies were begun by parents who developed a
product to meet their own needs, and then recognized a wider
potential, Mrs. Pepys said.
   One such firm is Decorate It! Inc., whose president, Angel
Martinez, said the company's wall decorating product was created
``out of pure need,'' specifically to avoid lengthy redecorating of
yet another room.''
   The system consists of a border and appliques with an adhesive
that allows them to be pulled off and reapplied ``more frequently
that anyone would every want to do it,'' said Martinez, who is also
a vice president of athletic shoemaker Reebok International Ltd.
   Also, joked Martinez, kids and parents can do the redecorating
together, ``a way to alleviate yuppie guilt'' over not spending
enough time with the children.
   Safety also has become a big issue in the industry. Cribs, for
example, no longer have finial posts or other sharp edges but are an
array of curves and rounded edges to prevent accidental cuts.
   Even bedding has been affected, Mrs. Pepys said, noting that
manufacturers have to be aware of the length of ties on crib bumper
pads to prevent accidental strangulation.
   The association has begun a certification program and hopes to
make consumers more aware of which products have been given a JPMA
seal of approval.
</TEXT>
