<FIRST>r f BC-ChryslerContract     09-17 0177</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Chrysler Contract,0185</SECOND>
<HEAD>Workers Overwhelmingly Approve Three-Year Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FENTON, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union employees at a Chrysler Corp. assembly
plant voted overwhelmingly to approve a three-year contract that was
reached hours before a strike deadline earlier in the week.
   A union spokesman said Saturday's vote was more than 90 percent
in favor of the three-year agreement, which affects about 3,800 of
the 4,400 workers at Chrysler's No. 1 plant in suburban St. Louis.
   The union said a major gain in the agreement is a provision for
relief for plant workers during heat waves. Complaints about what
workers called ``unbearable'' heat inside the plant prompted wildcat
walkouts in the past.
   Economic issues, such as wages and fringe benefits, are covered
in the national contract that expires in September 1990.
   Although details of the contract were not released, Local 136
President Ed Boyer said it contained provisions for more heat breaks
and more ice and water when heat becomes a problem inside the plant.
   The plant manufactures Dodge Daytona sports cars and Chrysler
LeBaron sports coupes and convertibles.
</TEXT>
