<FIRST>r f BC-Meridian-FirstPennsylvania     09-17 0204</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Meridian-First Pennsylvania,0213</SECOND>
<HEAD>Meridian Will Submit Another Bid To First Pennsylvania</HEAD>
<DATELINE>READING, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Meridian Bancorp Inc. said it will raise its
estimated $704 million bid for First Pennsylvania Corp. to beat an
offer made by CoreStates Financial Corp.
   ``We'll submit a higher bid; that will be in the near future,''
Meridian spokeswoman Doris Piasecki said Saturday. The Reading-based
bank holding company made its original offer for First Pennsylvania
in August.
   After the stock market closed Friday, CoreStates proposed a
stock-swap merger worth about $18.50 per common share for the
Philadelphia-based banking company, Piasecki said. The offer expires
at noon Monday, according to a news release from Meridian.
   First Pennsylvania's stock closed down 25 cents at $15.25 Friday
on the New York Stock Exchange.
   William Wolf, a spokesman for Philadelphia-based CoreStates, did
not return telephone messages left at his home over the weekend.
   First Pennsylvania had given Meridian until 5 p.m. Saturday to
respond to CoreStates' offer. Piasecki said management for the
company did not formally meet, but decided to raise its offer.
   She did not say when the offer will be made.
   Meridian said CoreStates requested a lock-up warrant, which would
be intended to thwart a hostile takeover by another party.
</TEXT>
