<FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-89 1943EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Belgium-NetherlandsMerger     09-17 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Belgium-Netherlands Merger,0206</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reports Say Merger Off Between Dutch, Belgian Banks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A proposed merger between the
Amsterdam-Rotterdam Bank NV, the Netherland's second-largest bank,
and Generale de Banque, Belgium's largest bank, has been called off,
media reports indicated Sunday.
   Both the Belgian national news agency, Belga, and the Rotterdam
newspaper Algemeen Dagblad said plans for the merger had been
shelved.
   According to the Belga report, negotiations between the two banks
ran into problems over legal, tax, and ``cultural'' differences.
   Spokesmen from Generale de Banque and Amro were not available for
comment. The two banks on Friday called a joint press conference for
Monday in Amsterdam.
   Neither press report cited its sources. But the Algemeen Dagblad
said Amro unions and worker councils were informed over the weekend
that the merger was off.
   The Belga report quoted ``several observers'' as saying that the
proposed merger had run into opposition from Compagnie Financiere de
Suez SA of France, which, through its majority stake in holding
company Societe Generale de Belgique, controls a 13-percent stake in
Generale de Banque.
   The Belga report said Suez preferred Generale de Banque link
itself instead to Banque Indosuez of France.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
